<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quakes Shake Islands South of Tokyo  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- More moderate earthquakes rattled a string of
volcanic islands south of Tokyo on Thursday, part of a series of
tremors that have hit the area for more than a month.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest temblor, with a preliminary magnitude of 5.1, was
centered six miles under the ocean floor off Niijima island, 105
miles south of Tokyo, the Meteorological Agency said. It struck at
6:42 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Takashi Sugimoto, a municipal official on Niijima, said there
were no immediate reports of damage or injuries. The island has 600
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's tremors, which also included a magnitude 4.6, were
among the tens of thousands registered in the islands since late
June, when a volcano on one of them rumbled back to life. Nearly
10,500 of the quakes have been strong enough to felt by humans.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is one of the world's most earthquake-prone nations as it
sits atop four tectonic plates, slabs of land that move across the
earth's surface.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
