<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Petrobras Fires Four Employees  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Government-owned oil conglomerate
Petrobras has fired four workers for failing to follow proper
procedure, triggering Brazil's worst oil spill in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Petrobras President Henri Phillipe Reichstul said an internal
investigation determined a botched pumping operation caused last
month's spill that spewed more than 1 million gallons of crude oil
into the Iguacu river.
</P>
<P>
   Before it was contained, the oil spill at the Getulio Vargas
refinery in Araucaria, about 435 miles southwest of Rio,
contaminated a 27-mile stretch of river, devastating wildlife and
sparking fears it would soil the world famous Iguacu falls.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation determined the spill occurred after an
employee failed to open a tank meant to receive the oil pumped from
the terminal. Two more employees were fired for failing to perform
routine safety checks that could have prevented the spill. Another
was fired for failing to detect the spill quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Petrobras has been fined $120 million by various state and
government agencies for environmental damage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 0031 </TRAILER>
