<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Army Moves in to Fiji Trouble Spot  </HEADLINE>
By ROHAN SULLIVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- The military sent troops to Fiji's second
largest island Thursday in a bid to put a stop to attacks against
ethnic Indians that have persisted since the Pacific nation's May
coup.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, Fiji's director of public prosecutions, Josaia
Naigolevu, announced that coup leader George Speight would be
arraigned Saturday on minor charges including unlawful assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Speight is under investigation for treason but has not yet been
charged with that offense, which carries a maximum sentence of
death.
</P>
<P>
   A company of soldiers was deployed to the northern island of
Vanua Levu to strengthen troop numbers there and end attacks on
ethnic Indians, said military spokesman Maj. Howard Politini. The
troops immediately arrested 30 suspected rebels and searched the
jungle for more, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At least one house was razed overnight, and armed gangs have for
weeks been terrorizing ethnic Indian families in towns on the
island, a stronghold of Speight support.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have moved into Vanua Levu in force and that should put an
end to the disturbances and enhance our search for weapons,''
Politini said.
</P>
<P>
   Raids, hostage-taking, theft, beatings and burnings have become
commonplace in small ethnic Indian-dominated rural communities
since a nationalist uprising in May which toppled Fiji's elected
government and bred more than 11 weeks of civil unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Failed businessman Speight led an armed gang into Parliament on
May 19 and held dozens of officials for two months, demanding
ethnic Indians be stripped of political rights. The military met
his demands for an amnesty and the scrapping of Fiji's multiracial
government.
</P>
<P>
   Speight claimed that ethnic Indian Fijians have too much power
and threaten indigenous Fijian culture. Ethnic Indians -- whose
ancestors were brought to Fiji in the 1870s by British colonialists
as indentured laborers -- make up 44 percent of Fiji's 814,000
population and dominate business and commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The political crisis has paralyzed the economy, dependent on
tourism and sugar exports, and brought sanctions by some nations
condemning Fiji's abandonment of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Speight was arrested last week and is the subject of a treason
investigation for allegedly threatening the life of President Ratu
Josefa Iloilo after his amnesty period expired. Speight and his key
advisers are being held on a prison island off Suva, the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 400 other hard-core rebel supporters were arrested in a
tear gas raid last week at a camp in Suva. The last of the rebels
were arraigned Thursday on charges of unlawful assembly, which
carries up to one year in prison. Most pleaded innocent and were
freed on bail.
</P>
<P>
   New Prime Minister Laisenia Qarase has promised to pursue a
nationalist agenda by appointing a commission to rewrite the
constitution to strengthen indigenous Fijians' hold on power before
elections are held, possibly in three years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
