<HEADLINE> Webber Testifies in Gambling Case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Former University of Michigan basketball star
Chris Webber testified Wednesday before a federal grand jury
investigating the alleged gambling activities of Ed Martin, a
former Wolverines booster.
</P>
<P>
   After testifying for nearly an hour, Webber said he will
cooperate with prosecutors who want to know about Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, 65, a retired Detroit electrician, is accused of
operating a lucrative numbers betting pool at the Ford Rouge plant
where he worked for 33 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''I answered all their questions, and I will help the
prosecutors as much as I can,'' Webber told The Detroit News.
</P>
<P>
   Webber, who plays for the NBA's Sacramento Kings, was scheduled
to testify last month but didn't show up for his court appearance.
On Wednesday, he arrived on time with his father, Mayce.
</P>
<P>
   Mayce Webber testified before the grand jury in June.
</P>
<P>
   Webber emerged from the U.S. Courthouse in Detroit smiling,
perhaps because, as he told the Detroit Free Press: ''I knew I was
not the one on the hot seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Webber is the second ex-Wolverines player called before the
grand jury at U.S. District Court. Earlier this summer Robert
Traylor, who plays for the Cleveland Cavaliers, answered questions
about his dealings with Martin.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the grand jury investigation, the FBI and IRS
also are looking into charges that Martin supplied players,
including Webber and Traylor, with large amounts of cash while they
were playing at Michigan. Failure to pay taxes on such cash gifts
would violate tax law.
</P>
<P>
   Traylor's lawyer, Steven F. Fishman of Detroit, also represents
Louis Bullock, another former Michigan player. Fishman said Bullock
will testify soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
