<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, Aug. 3, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Republicans Nominate Bush, Cheney
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Republicans awarded Texas Gov. George W. Bush their 2000
presidential nomination Wednesday night and chanted in unison as running mate
Dick Cheney ignited the convention with a partisan spark. Taunting the
Democrats, he said, ''It's time for them to go.'' Accepting his vice
presidential nomination, Cheney said Al Gore is ''trying to separate himself
from Bill Clinton's shadow, but it won't work. ''Somehow we will never see one
without thinking of the other,'' he said in a speech that drew waves of applause
from Republicans hungry to regain power after eight years out of the White
House.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gerald Ford Said Improving After Stroke
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Doctors say former President Gerald Ford is improving
after suffering one and possibly two small strokes at the Republican convention.
Ford, 87, was hospitalized Wednesday with slurred speech and difficulties with
balance. ''He should totally recover,'' said Dr. Robert Schwartzman, chief of
neurology at Hahnemann University Hospital.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Childhood Abuse, Adult Stress Linked
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Abuse in early childhood dramatically changes the brain
chemistry of women for life, making them more vulnerable to anxiety disorders
and more easily frustrated by stress as adults, a study suggests. Researchers
said the results could lead to profound advances in treatment for depression --
for women and men. The study was published Wednesday in the Journal of the
American Medical Association. Dramatic differences in women based on whether
they had been physically or sexually abused as children came to light when they
were asked to speak in front of a poker-faced audience and to solve tricky math
problems.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Army Moves in to Fiji Trouble Spot
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- The military sent troops to Fiji's second largest island
Thursday in a bid to put a stop to attacks against ethnic Indians that have
persisted since the Pacific nation's May coup. Also Thursday, Fiji's director of
public prosecutions, Josaia Naigolevu, announced that coup leader George Speight
would be arraigned Saturday on minor charges including unlawful assembly.
Speight is under investigation for treason but has not yet been charged with
that offense, which carries a maximum sentence of death.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
101 Dead in Attacks in Kashmir
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PAHALGAM, India (AP) -- Suspected Islamic guerrillas mowed down Hindu
pilgrims, police said, launching a 24-hour wave of violence that left 101 people
dead and the prospect of peace shattered in the Himalayan province of Kashmir.
Previously, a cease-fire by Kashmir's largest guerrilla group had raised hope
for peace after 11 years of fighting. Indian officials blamed Pakistan-based
guerrillas for the deaths, while witnesses said some of those killed were the
victims of reprisal shootings by Indian forces.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Report: Pinochet's Immunity Revoked
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Chile's Supreme Court has stripped Gen. Augusto
Pinochet of immunity from prosecution, paving the way for the former dictator to
stand trial on human rights charges, a lawyer and an official close to Pinochet
said. The court refused to publicly release its ruling. But lawyer Hugo
Gutierrez, who represents one of the plaintiffs accusing the 84-year-old general
of rights abuses, said he had ''fully confirmed'' the Supreme Court justices
removed Pinochet's immunity.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Canada Mulls Seizing US-Owned Ship
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Newfoundland (AP) -- Canada is considering boarding a U.S.-owned
cargo ship that is off its Atlantic coast and refuses to deliver its cargo of
Canadian military supplies because of a contract dispute. The GTS Katie, a
750-foot freighter, is 140 miles off Newfoundland in international waters,
holding onto a cargo that includes Canadian military's armored vehicles. A
Foreign Affairs Department spokesman said that Ottawa had received permission to
board the boat from the government of St. Vincent and the Grenadines, where the
boat is registered.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall Sharply
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks slid sharply lower Thursday morning, led by
selling in technology issues. The Nikkei shed 386.55 points to 15,837.64 at the
end of the morning session.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cardinals 10, Expos 7
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- Will Clark hit a home run in his first start for St. Louis
and Jim Edmonds homered twice and drove in five runs as the Cardinals beat the
Montreal Expos 10-7 Wednesday night. Clark, acquired from Baltimore on Monday's
to play first base in Mark McGwire's absence, went 3-for-4. He drove in two
runs.
AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS 
</P>
