<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fijian Indians Remain Under Attack  </HEADLINE>
By ROHAN SULLIVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   MUANIWENI, Fiji (AP) -- Two days after a screaming, cursing mob
torched the house his grandfather built in this lush farming
valley, Gayn Datt weeps at the sight of the ruins as they smolder
under a soft tropical rain.
</P>
<P>
   Datt and his wife were in their own home next door when the mob
arrived, local youths who have been terrorizing ethnic Indian
farmers in this valley for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ''They came up the hill. There was a lot of shouting and
swearing and they were throwing stones. They poured petrol all
around and then whoosh! it was all flames,'' Datt said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Raids, hostage-takings, beatings and burning attacks on the
ethnic Indians of Fiji's small rural communities have become
commonplace since a nationalist uprising on May 19 that toppled the
elected government and started more than 11 weeks of civil unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Datt's nephew and his three children had been living in his
grandfather's house, but fled a few days before the house was
torched because of previous threats by the youths.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have nothing left here,'' said Datt's wife, Sapaya. ''No
radio -- stolen. No TV. They killed our milking cow. We haven't
planted any crops for two months -- they told us not to.''
</P>
<P>
   Three homes were razed Monday night in Muaniweni, a hamlet an
hour's drive from Fiji's capital, Suva. The night before, two
houses were set on fire in a nearby town, and others were torched
in previous nights on the northern island of Vanua Levu.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Indians, descendants of indentured laborers brought to
work Fiji's sugar plantations from 1870s to the 1920s, now make up
44 percent of the South Pacific nation's 814,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Claiming ethnic Indians had too much power and were threatening
Fijian culture, failed businessman George Speight and armed
supporters stormed Parliament on May 19, taking dozens of officials
hostage. Speight demanded the multiracial constitution be scrapped
and the government, the first led by an ethnic Indian, ousted.
</P>
<P>
   Speight tapped a vein of resentment among Fijians toward ethnic
Indians, who have come to dominate business and commerce. A
nationalist rally in Suva the same day as the coup turned into a
riot. Indian-owned shops were looted and burned. Attacks on ethnic
Indians spread into the country.
</P>
<P>
   Fiji's military, which imposed martial law to try to stop the
unrest, agreed to Speight's demands to secure the freedom of the
last of the hostages on July 13. Since then, a strongly indigenous
Fijian Cabinet has been appointed to oversee the rewriting of the
constitution ahead of elections, possibly in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people -- mostly ethnic Indians -- are trying to flee
Fiji, afraid for their safety and the potential for financial ruin
following the near-collapse of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Fiji's tourism- and sugar export-dependent economy has been
crippled, and could be hurt even more by a large-scale exodus of
ethnic Indians. Australia, New Zealand, Britain, the United States
and France have imposed limited sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The military has cracked down, arresting Speight and hundreds of
the supporters in Suva. They also have quelled isolated pockets of
rebel support outside the capital, reclaiming a barracks on Vanua
Levu and the main hydropower station.
</P>
<P>
   But although they are becoming less common, attacks on rural
ethnic Indians continue.
</P>
<P>
   The unarmed police appear to have done little to stop the
attacks. At the police post at Muaniweni, inquiries about what was
being done to find those responsible for Monday's rampage were met
with blank stares and shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   Military spokesman Maj. Howard Politini said many of the farm
raids have nothing to do with Speight's cause. ''They are just a
criminal element who think they can get away with it and use the
coup as an excuse,'' Politini said.
</P>
<P>
   Politini said the military was moving in to restore security in
the areas of civil instability. There were no soldiers Wednesday in
Muaniweni.
</P>
<P>
   In some areas, ties between indigenous Fijians and ethnic
Indians have been strengthened by the trouble. Indigenous Fijians
have taken their neighbors in, providing them with shelter, food
and helping see off the gangs.
</P>
<P>
   But in Muaniweni, ethnic Indian families huddle together in
houses at night, or move into camps in the jungle around their
homes, Sapaya said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The police haven't done anything,'' she said. ''Most of the
locals around here have changed since the coup. They used to be
friendly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
