<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: Death Penalty Reprieve  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The last president to sign a death warrant for
a federal inmate was John F. Kennedy in 1963. One of President
Clinton's last Oval Office decisions may be whether to sign the
next one.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton on Wednesday postponed the scheduled execution of a
Texas drug dealer until Dec. 12, five weeks before the close of
Clinton's term. The inmate, Juan Raul Garza, had been set for
execution Aug. 5 at the federal penitentiary in Terre Haute, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Garza will use new government procedures to ask
Clinton for clemency, in much the same way that state death-row
inmates make last appeals to their governors.
</P>
<P>
   Garza's Houston attorney, Gregory Wiercioch, said he intends to
ask Clinton to commute Garza's sentence to life in prison without
the possibility of parole. The clemency request will focus on
whether minorities and residents of just a few, mostly southern,
states have been disproportionately sentenced to death under the
federal system.
</P>
<P>
   ''Racial disparities ... and where these cases come from makes a
big difference,'' in whether an inmate is sentenced to death,
Wiercioch said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is studying that same question but has
not yet issued a report.
</P>
<P>
   As the Garza execution loomed, the Clinton administration also
began reviewing federal procedures for carrying out the death
penalty, including the apparatus needed to file a clemency appeal.
Justice Department lawyers then decided to write a new set of
rules, which were released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The new, 10-page clemency guidelines allow an inmate 30 days to
file for clemency after an execution date is set. The Justice
Department then has 90 days to review the request and make a
recommendation to the president.
</P>
<P>
   The rules provide an opportunity for the inmate's attorney to
make an oral presentation to the Justice Department's pardon
attorney. They also provide a chance for families of the victims,
with the assistance of prosecutors in the case, to make their own
oral presentation to the pardon attorney.
</P>
<P>
   The White House indicated last month that Clinton would delay
Garza's execution so that he has the same opportunity to use the
new procedures as would any of the other 20 inmates on federal
death row.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents can grant a reprieve, as was last done in 1937 by
Franklin Delano Roosevelt, or they can commute an inmate's sentence
to less than death.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, a death penalty supporter, has not commented directly
on the Garza case.
</P>
<P>
   The 43-year-old inmate was convicted in August 1993 in
Brownsville, Texas, of killing three men between April 1990 and
January 1991. A 10-count indictment named him as the boss of a drug
ring that imported tons of marijuana into the United States between
1983 and 1993. He has lost appeals all the way up to the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Illinois Gov. George Ryan, a Republican, suspended
executions in that state until a panel could study its fairness.
Thirteen Illinois death row inmates have had their convictions
overturned since 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's decision helped propel the question of capital punishment
into the presidential campaign. Both Vice President Al Gore and his
Republican opponent, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, reiterated their
support for the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has expressed concern over racial disparities but does not
support a moratorium on executions. Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer
said the governor believes executions deter crime but also
''understands the complexity of each individual death penalty
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   One Democrat who has sought a moratorium on all executions, Sen.
Russ Feingold of Wisconsin, said Clinton's decision to delay the
Garza execution ''was the only fair and just thing to do,
particularly at a time when Americans are increasingly questioning
the fairness of our nation's administration of the death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Justice Department: http://www.usdoj.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 0102 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000803.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republican Motives Questioned  </HEADLINE>
By CALVIN WOODWARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The question hangs in the air and sometimes
gets answered without being posed: Why are you a Republican?
</P>
<P>
   It's asked directly or framed with raised eyebrows to racial
minorities, gays, people who want to preserve abortion rights,
people who want to clean up rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Condoleezza Rice, George W. Bush's international affairs adviser
and a black woman, answered the question at the Republican National
Convention without being asked, because she knows people wonder.
</P>
<P>
   ''I found a party that sees me as an individual, not as part of
a group,'' she said from the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Away from the stage, Randy Moody, co-chairman of Planned
Parenthood Republicans for Choice, said he gets the question all
the time.
</P>
<P>
   Moody recites his background: registered as a Republican in
1964, worked as a college Republican for Barry Goldwater, went to
the 1984 convention as a Nebraska delegate for Ronald Reagan. And
more.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not about to let the far right drive me out of the
Republican Party,'' he says. (Goldwater spoke from the right and in
defense of extremism, but favored abortion rights.)
</P>
<P>
   The party nowadays officially opposes affirmative action and gay
rights, wants abortion rights eliminated and excised a reference in
its platform to having a strong federal role in environmental
protection.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it tells minorities ''this is the party of
freedom and progress, and it is your home.'' Bush is trying to
appeal directly to them and to seem inclusive.
</P>
<P>
   ''When they reach out, we have to grab that hand,'' Shinae Chun,
an Illinois delegate, said of the party. She was happy to see more
fellow Asian-Americans in her state's crowd than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Some find their Republicanism a stigma at home.
</P>
<P>
   ''Being Hispanic and Republican in Chicago -- it's like a sin,''
said Rene Noriega, an alternate delegate.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Rep. Jim Kolbe is gay but what drives him on issues is
trade.
</P>
<P>
   He spent 12 years in Congress without discussing his sexuality
but came forward under threat of being ''outed'' when he spoke
against his party's Defense of Marriage Act opposing legal rights
for same-sex unions.
</P>
<P>
   He finds it inconsistent that his party wants the government out
of everybody's business, except when it comes to their personal
lives.
</P>
<P>
   He's a Republican nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, he says, seem to want the government out of
people's personal lives, but in their face in every other respect.
</P>
<P>
   On the environment, the Republicans were once strong. On the
Sierra Club's list of the 12 greatest environmental achievements of
the 20th century, President Nixon is credited with five.
</P>
<P>
   New York Republican Theodore Roosevelt IV, great grandson of
President Teddy Roosevelt, a father of the national park system,
reminded the party of that legacy in a speech. But his remarks were
lost in the buzz on the convention floor.
</P>
<P>
   The most prominent black Republican, retired Gen. Colin Powell,
criticized Republicans who attack affirmative action in an opening
night speech that cut through the buzz.
</P>
<P>
   Absorbing his words were two black members of the Utah
delegation, both raised as Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   James Evans, 36, who owns an investment company, grew up in
Orangeburg, S.C., home of two traditionally black colleges and many
black professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've only seen success within the black community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Winston Wilkinson, 55, was born in Cedar Heights, Md., in a
black section of town and says he ''never went within 20 feet of
whites until I went in the Navy in 1962.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Democratic President Kennedy, he carried the colors at
White House ceremonies. Then Wilkinson carried the Alabama state
flag during Democratic President Lyndon Johnson's inaugural parade,
and says segregationist Gov. George Wallace tried to take it from
his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson drifted into Republican politics in the 1970s. Today
he's drawn to GOP tenets of limited government, personal
responsibility and traditional values.
</P>
<P>
   ''My father always told me, 'Never be afraid to be different,'''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Associated Press writers Mark Warbis and
Christopher Wills contributed to this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
