<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guam GOP Seeks Recognition  </HEADLINE>
By TED ANTHONY
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Be honest, now: Do you know where Guam is?
Do you even know WHAT Guam is?
</P>
<P>
   In a geographically challenged nation where even questions about
Wyoming's whereabouts can consternate, many folks accosted at the
Republican National Convention had to admit ignorance. And that's
what Guam's GOP delegation is here to combat.
</P>
<P>
   They came from 17 hours away -- from America's most distant
territory. They rode three airplanes to get here. And what they're
doing this week, tiny as they are, is thinking big.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are proud and patriotic Americans living on America's
frontier,'' said Fred Castro, Guam's delegation chairman, who wears
a little gold elephant on his plum blazer. ''We're an integral part
of the American framework.''
</P>
<P>
   In the roiling sea of power brokers that is the Republican
convention, getting any attention can be a real trick. But David
Sablan, a 47-year-old insurance broker and Guam's GOP chairman, can
rattle off a dozen reasons why ''mainlanders'' should listen.
</P>
<P>
   ''When Americans say they have to protect their borders, they're
thinking of California,'' Sablan said. ''Guam can be our forward
post. We're not just a little supply base.''
</P>
<P>
   Guam, an island home to 145,000 people and the slogan ''Where
America's Day Begins,'' is the westernmost American territory,
ceded in 1898 after the Spanish-American War.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a possession, not a state. And its distance -- 8,902
miles from Congress -- makes it difficult for Guamanians to chart an
American destiny.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. military, for example, has long been a crucial part of
Guam. But 1990s base closures downsized the presence and left
islanders facing a ''brain drain.'' Guam had little recourse, and
the 1997 Asian economic crisis didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   ''This idea that federal employees are too expensive -- well,
guess what? The island is in turmoil,'' said Manny Cruz, a James
Earl Jones lookalike who heads the American Federation of
Government Employees in Guam and is an alternate delegate.
</P>
<P>
   Guam rises and falls on the mainland's fortunes. During and
after World War II, when many who fought in the South Pacific had
seen them firsthand, Guam and American Samoa seemed more real to
Americans. But in recent decades, many Guamanians feel distant
means ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ''When it comes to the territories, the American bias is more in
terms of apathy and ignorance,'' said Mike Young, a Penn State
Harrisburg political analyst.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason these Guamanians look to the Republican Party,
which they say treats them better than the government. Twelve of 15
seats in Guam's unicameral legislature are Republican-held. And
while its delegation to Congress has no vote, its four GOP
convention delegates cast votes as powerful, if not as numerous, as
any state's.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, in matching print shirts, they did just that,
giving their four votes to George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even though we are still maturing politically, we know who
will best serve our island and our nation as president,'' shouted
Guam's House speaker, Antonio R. Unpingco. On the same day, the new
GOP platform acknowledged Guam as a ''strategically vital U.S.
territory.''
</P>
<P>
   The Guamanians aren't the only ones saying ''we're here'' this
week. Representatives of America's Dangerfield Belt -- those who
feel they don't get no respect -- are out in force, fighting the
assumption of irrelevance that Comedy Central's Jon Stewart
personified when he described the convention as a ''week-long
festival of diversity, inclusion and the obligatory nod to American
Samoa.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday evening, for example, found District of Columbia
Councilman David Catania on the convention floor urging that
district residents be allowed to vote in Congress. The U.S. Virgin
Islands delegation is here. And from Puerto Rico, the most
politically powerful of the non-mainland territories, came delegate
Miriam Ramirez, a statehood advocate upset she can't be heard in
Washington -- even though she's an American.
</P>
<P>
   ''So many people here think we're foreign,'' Ramirez said.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates from American Samoa, whose territory was misspelled as
''Somoa'' in the official media guide, were more sanguine. Amata
Radewagen, who co-presided over the nominating process Wednesday
night in a long dress festooned with pachyderms, said her
appointment as a convention officer -- the first from a territory --
''speaks volumes.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm from a little island, and here I am,'' she said. ''It's a
recognition of what the Republican Party thinks of the territories.
Awareness is increasing every day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 0111 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000803.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Troops Restore Order To Venezuela  </HEADLINE>
By ALEXANDRA OLSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- A shaky calm has returned to
Venezuela's provinces after violent protests that broke out over
disputed election results.
</P>
<P>
   At least one person was killed and a dozen others injured
Tuesday when supporters of President Hugo Chavez clashed with
opposition backers in several states where results of gubernatorial
races were being contested.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of army troops were called in to restore order.
</P>
<P>
   Several incumbent opposition governors who lost by thin margins
in Sunday's elections said they would challenge the results in
court but urged their supporters to refrain from violence.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuelans re-elected Chavez by a landslide in Sunday's polls,
which were required by a new constitution Chavez pushed through
last year that called for public offices to be ''re-legitimized.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez broke into Venezuela's national scene eight years ago by
staging a failed military coup. He became president in February
1999 promising a ''social revolution'' for the poor, and during the
latest campaign repeatedly called opposition candidates
''counterrevolutionaries.''
</P>
<P>
   International observers said the elections appeared relatively
transparent, but urged an investigation into complaints of
irregularities. Several opposition leaders have asked the foreign
monitors to stay to scrutinize the outcome more carefully.
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Calderon, governor of the western state of Tachira, said
he will challenge a controversial decision by the electoral board
to give his opponent the votes of a third candidate who dropped
out, thus denying him re-election.
</P>
<P>
   In the Andean state of Merida, ousted governor William Davila
huddled with his lawyers to outline a strategy to contest the
results, which had him losing by a mere 1,686 votes. Davila said
9,500 ''invalid'' votes suggest fraud. With Davila's defeat,
Chavez' adversaries would lose one of their most respected and
popular leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ''Davila thought it was impossible for him to lose. He has the
right to protest because this is a democracy but it is
irresponsible for him to call this fraud,'' said the man who beat
him in the polls, Florencio Porras, a Chavez supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's clashes between Davila's and Chavez' supporters
injured nine people, blocked roads and forced local businesses to
close. Head of Merida military operations Jorge Garcia said the
violence subsided Wednesday and traffic and business activity
returned to normal.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez said Tuesday his coalition would continue fighting for
its candidates in disputed elections. ''We're consolidating our
revolution, and like any battle, we have to care for it up to the
last bit of territory,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez' leftist political coalition won 14 of the country's 23
states and a simple majority in Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 0112 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000803.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Candidates Seek Donors  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN SOLOMON
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The congressional candidate listened
patiently to the Arkansas businessman talk about his heart attack,
his insurance business, his taxes. He reached for a notebook in his
breast pocket. ''Do you have a card?'' he interjected.
</P>
<P>
   Though Mike Ferguson, a Republican, wants to represent New
Jersey, he didn't miss the chance to jot down the name of a
possible donor from halfway across the land. ''I'll keep you
posted,'' Ferguson promised.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, he strode across a stage, took a quill from a Ben
Franklin impersonator and signed his name on a ''Small Business
Declaration of Freedom'' -- as hundreds of business owners watched.
</P>
<P>
   It's a quadrennial ritual for congressional wannabes: flocking
to the nominating conventions and working the periphery, hoping to
connect with out-of-state donors and drum up money for fall
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ''The real action at this convention is taking place outside the
convention hall, in the hospitality suites and the railroad cars,
all these areas where lobbyists are talking to lawmakers,'' said
Larry Makinson, head of the Center for Responsive Politics, which
studies political fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson, a teacher making his second bid for Congress in a
closely watched congressional race, has worked a lengthy list of
cocktail receptions with his chief fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got stacks of business cards, and we'll follow up once
we get back home,'' explained William A. Milligan, Ferguson's
finance director.
</P>
<P>
   John Dorso, a GOP House candidate in North Dakota, was equally
busy.
</P>
<P>
   He went to a luncheon thrown by House Speaker Dennis Hastert,
got introduced to a lobbyist for DaimlerChrysler by House Majority
Leader Dick Armey and hooked up with General Motors executives
through aides of House Republican Whip Tom DeLay.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was just glad-handing folks, and handing out (contribution)
envelopes,'' Dorso said.
</P>
<P>
   Such candidates are getting plenty of help. The Republican Party
and many interest groups, like the National Federation of
Independent Business, which sponsored the event Ferguson attended,
have staged events in Philadelphia to facilitate all the hand
shaking and business-card-swapping.
</P>
<P>
   And though leaders of the sometimes unpopular GOP-led Congress
have been conspicuously absent from the televised portions of the
convention, they have worked furiously behind the scenes to help
candidates like Ferguson find national donors.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson was selected as one of a few GOP aspirants given a
moment on stage during the televised portion of the convention to
introduce themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is all by design,'' explained Rep. J.C. Watts, the No. 4
Republican in the House. ''Members don't mind. And putting our
newest challengers up front helps to show the country and those who
support us that we have diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaking hands over and over again, Ferguson has a finely honed
pitch. To some, he harkens to his background as a teacher because
''businesses understand we need new workers prepared for the 21st
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Other times, he stresses his experience starting a small
consulting business and his understanding of how too much
regulation and excessive taxes can stifle innovation.
</P>
<P>
   James Davis, the Arkansas insurance businessman who talked to
Ferguson at the small business reception, found the candidate
sympathetic to his hopes that Congress eliminate the estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you reach this level and you have a little bit of
success, then they want to take it away from you,'' Davis lamented.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson gave an understanding nod, before moving on to greet
others. Eventually, he bumped into Rep. Bob Barr of Georgia,
offering a succinct reason why he had to work so many receptions
this week.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just spent $900,000 to win the primary. And now I'm going to
need $1.2 million for the fall,'' Ferguson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 0115 </TRAILER>
