<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fed: Big Banks Charge Big Fees  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN CRUTSINGER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- America's largest banks charge significantly
more for services than smaller banks that do business in only one
state, the Federal Reserve has found in an annual survey of bank
fees.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed report, released Wednesday, also found that the number
of banks offering free checking account services dropped to 10.8
percent in 1999, compared with 17.3 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The number of savings and loans with free checking account
services rose to 30 percent last year, compared with 23.4 percent
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   On the difference in fees between big banks that operate in a
number of states and small banks, the Fed said, ''Most of the fees
charged by multistate banks were on average significantly higher
than those charged by single-state banks.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed report found the average bounced check fee at a
single-state bank was $17.04 last year, compared with $21.80
charged by big banks.
</P>
<P>
   Small banks charged on average $14.50 for a stop-payment order,
compared with $20.10 for big banks, the central bank found.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, based on inquiries with 1,000 financial
institutions, also showed that more banks offer minimum-balance
accounts, in which customers pay flat monthly fees as long as their
balances remain above a certain amount.
</P>
<P>
   It found 40.6 percent of banks offering such accounts, compared
with 35.6 percent in 1998. The average monthly charge dropped last
year by 28 cents to $6.15, compared with $6.43 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The latest report will be the Fed's final survey on bank fees
unless Congress reauthorizes the annual review.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates said the disparity illustrates a need for
legislative oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ''The report continues to show that bigger banks continue to
charge bigger fees,'' said Edmund Mierzwinski, consumer program
director for U.S. Public Interest Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   Mierzwinski said his group, which also has studied bank charges,
has found that more banks charge customers for services that once
were free, such as assessments for transactions involving tellers
or the return of canceled checks.
</P>
<P>
   ''Regular checking account service fees are not going up that
much, but banks are adding new fees. You are getting less but
paying more,'' Mierzwinski said.
</P>
<P>
   Banking industry officials defended the more prevalent fees as a
way to hold down basic charges.
</P>
<P>
   John Hall, a spokesman for the American Bankers Association,
said a survey the ABA did last month showed that 59 percent of bank
customers pay $3 or less for monthly bank services.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bank fee structures have really gone from a one-size-fits-all
approach to a pay-as-you-go approach,'' Hall said. ''You only pay
for the services you use, rather than having one fee structure
subsidize everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Federal Reserve: http//www.federalreserve.gov
</P>
<P>
   Public Interest Research Group:
http://www.pirg.org/reports/consumer/bankfees/index.html
</P>
<P>
   American Bankers Association:
http://www.aba.com/aba/AboutABA/homepage.asp
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 0115 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000803.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Leaders In Convention Background  </HEADLINE>
By CURT ANDERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Attentive viewers of the Republican National
Convention might have caught the brief speech Wednesday night by
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, one of the few GOP leaders from
Capitol Hill who got a share of the prime-time limelight.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, Lott, of Mississippi, and House Speaker Dennis Hastert
of Illinois have been relegated to mundane convention tasks such as
wielding the opening gavel. House Majority Leader Dick Armey and
Majority Whip Tom DeLay, both from George W. Bush's home state of
Texas, haven't been seen at the podium at all.
</P>
<P>
   But the No. 4 House Republican and only black GOP member of
Congress, Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, has appeared regularly to
introduce speakers and perform other duties in prime time, along
with Reps. Jennifer Dunn of Washington state and Henry Bonilla of
Texas, a Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, each of the three have the title ''permanent co-chair''
of the convention, in yet another carefully scripted effort by the
GOP to appeal to minorities, women and groups that don't always
vote Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of dark-suited lawmakers intoning their Capitol Hill
rhetoric, Republicans found ''real people'' to give short addresses
about tax cuts, reducing government regulations, welfare and Social
Security. Dunn said this lack of prominent legislative talk was
part of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wanted this to be a real-life convention,'' Dunn said. ''We
didn't want just policy people up there. We wanted people who are
really living it.''
</P>
<P>
   If they feel slighted, no congressional leaders have said so
publicly or privately, several lawmakers said Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''My personal opinion is, people see enough of us on C-SPAN,''
said Rep. Jo Ann Emerson, R-Mo. ''This is a time for the Bush
campaign to talk about what they want to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   For House members, all 435 of whom are up for re-election this
year, the conventions are more valuable for the fund-raisers
organized by DeLay and other leaders and the contact with delegates
who can help with their campaigns back home.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign has regular contact with Capitol Hill leaders
at the staff level and coordinates with the committees that direct
money and resources into congressional races. Bush himself has kept
Congress at arm's length, but there have been no recurrences of
last year's criticism that GOP leaders would ''balance the budget
on the backs of the poor'' if they pushed to curtail a low-income
tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   ''Since then, I haven't heard a lot of grumbling,'' said Rep.
Steve Chabot of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   If they haven't been picked for prime time, GOP leaders have run
a popular party circuit. Hastert attracted big-money donors to a
morning fly-fishing trip at nearby Valley Forge and the ''Lott
Hop'' early 1960s theme party over the weekend was packed with
revelers. DeLay has held a series of events at a site just outside
the convention hall and Armey is hosting a big country music soiree
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every event is a political event. That's what it's all about,
introducing people,'' said Sen. Rick Santorum of Pennsylvania.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
