<HEADLINE> Countries Seek Democracy Lessons  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Macedonia sent an observer to the Republican
National Convention to get some tips on democracy-building because
''the U.S. way is the way to freedom.'' Azerbaijan wanted to get up
to speed ahead of its parliamentary elections this fall.
</P>
<P>
   They are among the hundreds of ambassadors, lawmakers and other
government officials from around the world who are in Philadelphia
for a first-hand look at the American political process.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are trying to establish a system of democracy,'' said
Macedonian observer Igor Popov, whose country didn't exist the last
time the Republicans won the White House. ''We base our model on
the U.S. model,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Azerbaijan sent two embassy officials in advance of its
parliamentary elections -- contests the opposition is already
criticizing as undemocratic because of laws that would prevent some
parties from participating.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have only eight years of independence,'' said Elmar
Mamedyarov, an embassy counselor. ''We are still in transition from
communism to democracy. ... It's quite important, these events, (to
see) if they can be incorporated or not.''
</P>
<P>
   China sent a 14-member delegation to Philadelphia. ''The trip is
designed in effect to educate, in a very discreet and courteous
way,'' said Allen Weinstein, president of the Washington-based
Center for Democracy, which is hosting the Chinese delegation here
and at the Democratic convention in Los Angeles. ''The key is to
recognize that this is a long-range process. It's not going to
transform itself in a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Party officials say the number of foreign dignitaries
attending this year's convention is greater than previous years --
in part because ambassadors could make the trip easily from
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Ambassadors from 135 countries and their spouses are arriving
Thursday on a special luxury train for a day of foreign policy
briefings, sightseeing, dinner and watching George W. Bush's speech
accepting the Republican presidential nomination. Corporate members
of Potomac Exchange, a nonpartisan group, are funding the trip.
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand's U.S. ambassador, James Bolger, said he was
attending both the Republican and Democratic conventions to assess
the candidates' trade, security, economic and foreign policies and
how they might affect his country.
</P>
<P>
   Chen Gaoshan, a member of the Chinese delegation, was more
blunt: ''We are here to get to know some information about party
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   But the 12-member parliamentary delegation from across the
Taiwan Straits said it was more interested in influencing party
policy than learning about it.
</P>
<P>
   Parris Chang, chairman of the foreign relations committee in
Taiwan's parliament, said he hoped to convince Republican
decisionmakers that their support of a ''one China'' policy was
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   His delegation hosted a cocktail reception at Philadelphia's
Academy of Fine Art. ''The Bush administration should go a huge
step further to differentiate itself from the Clinton
administration,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Pomper, a professor of political science at Rutgers
University, said foreign governments could learn from the American
political process.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a country in which we pass power uncomplainingly,''
Pomper said. ''And when you think of Serbia ... this is a very
relatively rare and very precious thing and we do have something to
offer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 0119 </TRAILER>
