<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dot-Com Convention Coverage Varies  </HEADLINE>
By ANICK JESDANUN
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Take an instant poll. Chat with fellow viewers.
Play a game of ''electoral chess.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet offers all this and more in its attempt to promote
greater audience participation in the Republican National
Convention. The interactive features return Thursday night, as
George W. Bush gives his acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   But promises often sound better than reality. The convention has
been highly scripted, and the Internet by itself was powerless to
change that. Even the Net's bells and whistles couldn't improve its
relevance.
</P>
<P>
   Chat rooms allowed viewers to set the agenda, and participants
generally chose to discuss anything but the convention.
</P>
<P>
   At CNN, MSNBC and Pseudo, chat rooms often became forums to bash
Bush, President Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and fellow Internet
users.
</P>
<P>
   During Dick Cheney's speech Wednesday accepting the GOP vice
presidential nomination, chatters continued off-topic discussions.
More often than not, the few comments on Cheney's record were
unrelated to his floor remarks.
</P>
<P>
   One chatter going by the name ''Boring'' kept interjecting such
comments as ''Cheney is boring.'' Another chatter responded, ''Gore
invented boring.'' Yet another, ''Boring is boring.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Roberts, a political communications specialist at the
University of Florida, said the text-based assaults reduce the
Net's usefulness.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we are to have substantive discussions and this be truly
interactive, we must learn civility.''
</P>
<P>
   TV call-in programs on C-SPAN and other cable stations offered
viewer participation with fewer distractions.
</P>
<P>
   Some sites had instant polls to engage viewers. America Online
visitors voted on such items as pro wrestler The Rock's role as a
convention speaker. AOL immediately displayed results and discussed
them with its guest, former Miss America Nicole Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   But such online polls, even on meaningful topics, are
unscientific and reveal nothing about the mood of the general
electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, news organizations tried to marry television and
the Net. Pseudo's David Bohrman suggested earlier that viewers turn
off TV and tune in to his site's TV-like coverage. But viewers
could have missed an entire speech just getting their computers
configured properly.
</P>
<P>
   C-SPAN repeatedly directed viewers to its Web site to ask
questions and join a chat. Cable's Fox News Channel displayed an
e-mail address and Web site. Peter Jennings concluded the evening
news with the site for ABC News.
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC's site allowed Internet users to send questions to NBC
News anchor Tom Brokaw and its floor reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Also at MSNBC was an ''electoral chess'' feature that lets
viewers play campaign manager, figuring how to get the 270
electoral votes needed to win the presidential election. An online
quiz on convention history required viewers to watch cable TV for
answers. CNN's site had an adjustable map of the convention hall.
</P>
<P>
   SpeakOut.com promised MSNBC viewers an on-screen dial to
register what they liked or disliked about each speaker. But, in a
reminder of technology's limits, the site crashed shortly before
Cheney spoke.
</P>
<P>
   Yet broadcast veteran Sam Donaldson opened a Webcast at the ABC
News site with a prediction.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm telling you, folks, in another four or eight, 12 years at
the outside, there won't be any convention on television,'' he
said. ''It will be all on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: GOP official site: http://gopconvention.com
</P>
<P>
   C-SPAN: http://c-span.org
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC: http://decision2000.msnbc.com
</P>
<P>
   ABC: http://abcnews.go.com
</P>
<P>
   Fox News: http://foxnews.com/elections
</P>
<P>
   CNN: http://cnn.com/allpolitics
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
