<HEADLINE> Peaceful Protests at Convention  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER NEWTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- With more than 300 activists still in jail,
protests aimed at the Republican convention were quiet and peaceful
Wednesday, a day after demonstrators clashed with police and
snarled traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we may have disorganized them yesterday,'' Deputy
Commissioner Sylvester Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   A few small protests popped up around town, and activists held
banners and signs at several locations to greet George W. Bush, who
arrived Wednesday to accept the party's nomination for president.
</P>
<P>
   The quiet demonstrations contrasted to Tuesday evening's mayhem,
which led to 300 arrests. At least 10 demonstrators were charged
with felonies for assaulting an officer.
</P>
<P>
   Those arrested were not expected to be released from jail before
the convention ends Thursday. Processing is delayed because many
have refused to give their names, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner John Timoney was one of 15 officers slightly
injured in clashes with protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, about 40 demonstrators denouncing the death penalty
and calling attention to other issues chanted and waved banners at
an entrance to a downtown arena when Bush arrived for a noon
fund-raiser. They were surrounded by about 50 police officers as
Bush entered through another door.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact is these people don't represent the people of this
country and they are constantly arguing in favor of corporate
America,'' said 16-year-old Tuck Young. ''We have to hit the
streets and try to gain the support of the people of this nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, about 120 Democrats posted 20 flags representing
Spanish-speaking countries outside the Philadelphia Museum of Art,
where Bush addressed a Hispanic audience. The demonstrators said
they were unhappy with Bush's record on Latino issues in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia officials said most convention delegates did not
even notice Tuesday's protests unless they watched television.
</P>
<P>
   ''People who came into Philadelphia today didn't even realize
that anything happened in Philadelphia overnight,'' Philadelphia
Managing Director Joe Martz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
