<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Delegates Re-enact 'Rocky's Run'  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER NEWTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Bounding up the steps, sweating in the
stifling midday heat, Jose Mendoza revels in the struggle to fill
the shoes of his favorite icon.
</P>
<P>
   After running six miles through the crowded streets, the
74-year-old fitness buff used a final burst of energy to leap up
the 80 steps of the Philadelphia Museum of Art, just like a certain
fictional boxer who will forever be associated with the city.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who thinks the movie ''Rocky'' has been forgotten only
needs to sit on the city's most famous stairs for 10 minutes, where
he lives on with his fans. Every. Single. Day.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza, an adviser to the Montana delegation, was no exception.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway up the stairs, a group of art connoisseurs sneer at the
shameless celebration of pop culture.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza continues, undaunted.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty more steps.
</P>
<P>
   Three street sweepers perched on a fountain break into the
familiar theme -- da-da-da, da-da-dum.
</P>
<P>
   Jumping up the last steps, Mendoza's face bursts into a smile
and he victoriously trots around in a circle, finally leaping into
the air with his hands toward the sky.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to make this run just like the main man did before
his big fight,'' Mendoza said, huffing and puffing with his hands
on his knees. ''He did it and obviously it worked for him.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Rocky,'' which stared Sylvester Stallone as a
tough-guy-turned-boxer, won the Oscar for Best Picture in 1976, the
year it was released. In the scene before the boxer's climactic
fight, Rocky runs through urban Philadelphia, and finally, up the
steps.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 years and four sequels later, out-of-towners still
make special trips to the stairs just for the purpose of running to
the top.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just a movie, but if you see it enough times, it begins
to seem real,'' said Darrel Hargrove, a 27-year-old lawyer who
makes the run daily. ''When you think of these steps, you think of
Rocky.''
</P>
<P>
   In the third movie, the city puts a sculpture of the boxer at
the top of the steps. That statue stood on the steps, in real life,
for more than a decade. The museum made the decision to remove the
statue two years ago. It remains outside a sports arena, but some
fans still grumble about it.
</P>
<P>
   ''They should have left it here,'' said 44-year-old Timothy
Smith, a lawyer. ''It wasn't art, but it was about courage and
determination and inner strength, which are all very beautiful
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Art lovers have long questioned the memorial to a fictional
character.
</P>
<P>
   ''It wasn't even that good of a sculpture,'' said Jessica
Hansen. ''It doesn't look like him. Maybe people should spend more
time inside the museum.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 0135 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000803.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Delegates Reflect on Freedom  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Solomon Yue remembers electing
his class
president in school.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ''The teacher would come to you and say, 'You vote for this
guy,''' he says. That's the way things were in China, where he grew
up during the Cultural Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't know anything about freedom, about the democratic
process,'' says Yue, now 41 and an Oregon delegate to the
Republican convention. Few outside his delegation know how long Yue
has struggled to be able to make his vote count.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't tell his story often, and when he's asked he starts
slowly and chooses his words. His grandfather was a tailor -- a
capitalist -- and when the Cultural Revolution began in 1976, his
whole family was suspect.
</P>
<P>
   When Yue was 7 he watched Red Guards storm his house and destroy
everything of value. School ended that year, and re-education camp
began. He was forced to work in factories and in the fields, eating
only rice and sleeping on dirt floors covered with straw.
</P>
<P>
   The political re-education was a brainwashing, Yue said -- but it
certainly didn't take. Teachers tried everything to shut him up.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was labeled a troubled kid, a spiritual polluter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, the revolution ended with the death of its leader, Mao
Tse-tung, and the arrest of his supporters. The pressure eased on
Yue, although he still rebelled.
</P>
<P>
   His grandfather, who had earlier fled to Hong Kong, arranged a
scholarship for him to Alaska Pacific University. He arrived in
Alaska knowing two English phrases: Thank you and Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   He was fascinated by a man on TV who seemed to speak about
everything Yue had gotten in trouble for saying in China. The year
was 1980 and the man was Ronald Reagan. Yue asked a friend to
translate and was riveted by Reagan's speeches on freedom and
capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was almost my entire life's thinking being ratified
somehow, being confirmed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He worked two jobs to put himself through college and got
married. In 1990, Yue and his wife, a doctor, moved to Salem, Ore.,
where she opened a clinic and he started a latex glove business.
</P>
<P>
   This convention, Yue's first as a delegate, has been dismissed
by some as a pep rally. Yue can't stand that kind of talk.
</P>
<P>
   ''It really is to protect freedom,'' he said. ''To be able to
sort through what is real, and what is not.''
</P>
<P>
   By REBECCA COOK
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Hours after grenades showered a seven-car procession on a Cuban
road, destroying six vehicles but missing the one carrying Fidel
Castro, a conspirator got a phone call.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're coming for you,'' said the voice on the other end.
</P>
<P>
   No longer could Manuel Rebuelta, Cuba's minister of health,
remain cloaked in the perception he still supported Castro's
revolution. He grabbed two machine guns, kissed his wife goodbye,
and fled for the Brazilian embassy.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 years later, Rebuelta is engaged in a process to
nominate a democratic president. Make no mistake, though -- that's
''democratic'' with a little ''d.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebuelta has become one of Georgia's most active Republicans and
is an alternate delegate at GOP's national convention.
</P>
<P>
   In the early days, Rebuelta was on Castro's side in the revolt
against the dictatorship of Fulgencio Batista.
</P>
<P>
   Castro tapped Rebuelta, a doctor, as the movement's health
minister because Rebuelta was already in charge of the hospitals
where wounded rebels were taken. But when Castro ordered a shipment
of unsanitary beef exported to the United States, Rebuelta refused
to sign off, enraging the leader.
</P>
<P>
   Rebuelta decided to take a chance and call on a fellow official
who he suspected also had concerns about Castro's plans. His hunch
was correct -- the official had been stockpiling weapons to stage a
revolt against Castro.
</P>
<P>
   When their plot failed, Rebuelta escaped to Brazil, where he
spent three years before heading to Puerto Rico and then Atlanta.
His parents and wife joined him there later.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a great enthusiast, a smiling spokesperson for
anti-Communism,'' said Georgia Republican chairman Chuck Clay.
''Nobody can question whether he has paid his dues.''
</P>
<P>
   By JEFFREY McMURRAY
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Winston Wilkinson and James Evans, two black alternate delegates
from overwhelmingly white Utah, took very different paths to the
Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   The two men, from a state where blacks make up less than 1
percent of the population, both began their political lives as
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson, 55, said he has worked hard to overcome racism.
Eventually, he converted to Mormonism and went to work for
church-owned Brigham Young University. He is a candidate for Salt
Lake County Council.
</P>
<P>
   Evans, 36, who plans to run for state GOP chairman next summer,
is a lifelong Baptist who owns his own investment company. He
insists that he has never felt the effects of segregation or racism
-- not where he grew up in Orangeburg, S.C., or in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't necessarily believe that a lot of the negative
experiences are because of race. We've been taught to discount
personality,'' he said. ''Whether you're black, white, conservative
or liberal, that shouldn't effect whether you're liked or
disliked.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson was born in Cedar Heights, Md., where he said a
section of town fenced off with barbed wire kept blacks segregated.
''I never went within 20 feet of whites until I went in the Navy in
1962.''
</P>
<P>
   He was assigned to the military honor guard in Washington, D.C.,
and President Kennedy made him a member of the special unit that
carries the colors at White House ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   He later became a Muslim and a follower of Malcolm X.
Eventually, after getting business and law degrees from Howard
University, he got involved in Republican politics. He works as a
fund-raiser at Brigham Young.
</P>
<P>
   Both men welcome George W. Bush's efforts to show the GOP's
diversity and attract more minorities, moderates and independent
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been waiting so long for the party to put this kind of
face on it,'' Wilkinson said. ''I'm not going to let Democrats tear
that down.''
</P>
<P>
   By MARK WARBIS
</P>
</TEXT>
