<HEADLINE> Roll Call Delivers Amusement  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE FEINSILBER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Ohio: ''The state that is earning a
reputation as the reading state of America...''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma: ''A state that understands the future belongs to
conservative governance...''
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico: ''The window of American democracy in the
Caribbean...''
</P>
<P>
   South Dakota: ''The pheasant capital of the world....''
</P>
<P>
   For the nostalgic, it is one of the few reminders of how
conventions used to be. For old timers' sake, choreographers of the
Republican convention allowed the roll call of the states one more
dance.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a streamlined convention, the roll call offered the
chance to engage in old-fashioned, not-made-for-television,
oratorical horseplay, a rolling reminder that the United States
remains composed of 50 individual and somewhat eccentric entities.
</P>
<P>
   The powers that reconfigured the convention to fit a ''different
kind of Republican'' allowed this institution to stay, even if
truncated over four nights out of fear of boredom.
</P>
<P>
   And so Wednesday night the states that came toward the end of
the alphabet got the chance to point with pride and make puns with
impunity. After all, it occurred before prime time, and the
networks weren't watching.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee took its turn to chide the forthcoming Democratic
presidential candidate, of indisputable Tennessee roots, Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Said Tennessee: ''We look forward to his return to Tennessee as
a private citizen in January 2001.''
</P>
<P>
   North Dakota made hay of its rural heritage. It called itself
''the safest state in the union,'' and said, ''We have clean air
and short commutes.''
</P>
<P>
   And Texas, home of the party's new nominee, George W. Bush,
permitted itself to engage in some geopolitical braggadocio: ''From
the vast prairies of the Red River country to the piney woods of
East Texas, from the rolling hills of Central Texas to the sandy
beaches of the Texas Gulf Coast, from the booming metropolises of
Dallas and Houston to the towns that border on the Rio Grande ... A
Texas where no dream is too small and no dream is too grand ... A
Texas where diversity is more than a goal, it's who we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe because the gavel was fixed on keeping to schedule and
because it comes near the end of the call, Utah made a short claim
none could dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Utah called itself ''the only state that starts with 'U.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
