<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two men arrested in 1999 death of graduate student  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - More than a year after Amy Watkins was fatally
stabbed in the back with a 10-inch kitchen knife as she walked to
her Brooklyn apartment, two men have been arrested and charged with
her murder.
</P>
<P>
   David Jamison, 27, of Brooklyn, was charged Wednesday with
first-degree murder, first-degree robbery and criminal possession
of a weapon in the graduate student's death. Felix Rodriguez, 20,
of Brooklyn, was charged early Thursday with second-degree murder,
first-degree robbery and criminal possession of a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   A third man was still being questioned in the case early
Thursday at the 77th Precinct in Brooklyn and had not been charged,
said Sgt. Elias Nikas, a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Jamison was picked up for questioning Wednesday thanks to
several tips to police, including some from the Crime Stoppers hot
line. He had previously been arrested for selling drugs, petit
larceny and robbery.
</P>
<P>
   A police source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Jamison and two other men saw Watkins walk by the restaurant they
were in on March 8, 1999, and decided she would be an easy robbery
target. Watkins apparently struggled with her attacker and she was
stabbed once, the source said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Watkins, the victim's father, said in a telephone
interview from his Manhattan home that he was completely surprised
when police called him about 1 p.m. Wednesday to tell them about
the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought someday something would happen, but I really didn't
have a lot of hope,'' he said. He expressed gratitude to the police
for never giving up on the case.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter's death horrified the city and her neighbors in
Prospect Heights, a quiet neighborhood of gentrified brownstones a
short subway ride from Manhattan. Her slaying came at a time when
the city was in the midst of a dramatic decrease in violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins, 26 and from Kansas, was studying for her masters in
social work, counseling battered women and working with children as
an intern at the New Settlement Community Center in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   She had taken the subway from the Bronx, where she organized a
meeting for parents about their children's reading scores. She was
attacked as she walked home from the subway station, after stopping
for some groceries shortly before 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   She was unconscious when passers-by found her on the sidewalk -
some residents said they had heard a woman scream. Watkins lived
with a roommate in an apartment building about two blocks from
where she was stabbed.
</P>
<P>
   She was born in Illinois but raised in Topeka, Kan., and
graduated from the University of Kansas. She moved to New York in
1997 after living briefly in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins was a second-year graduate student at Hunter College's
School of Social Work, had an internship at the center and had
started working there in September 1998.
</P>
<P>
   She was buried in suburban St. Louis, where her mother, Margaret
Tafoya, and her stepfather, John Tafoya, live. Lawrence Watkins
teaches at Dominican Academy in Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
