<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suharto Charged With Corruption  </HEADLINE>
By IRWAN FIRDAUS
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Prosecutors on Thursday charged former
President Suharto with siphoning off $570 million in state funds
and planned to take him to court within days.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has been formally charged,'' said Umbu Laga Lazore, a
member of the investigative team that probed Suharto's wealth.
''From now on Suharto's status is as a defendant.''
</P>
<P>
   The team handed over the case to prosecutors at Suharto's home
in central Jakarta where he has been held under house arrest for
several months. The officials held talks with the former dictator's
attorneys, who maintain Suharto is too sick to face trial because
of recent strokes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Suharto has brain damage,'' said his chief counsel, Juan Felix
Tampubolon.
</P>
<P>
   Another defense lawyer, Mohamad Assegaf, said Suharto fully
cooperated with the officials on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of police were deployed as a precaution against
possible protests by students who want him tried immediately, not
only for corruption but also for human rights violations.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto is accused of using charities under his control to
siphon off the money during his 32-year iron-fisted rule. Suharto,
who was forced to quit after riots in May 1998, has denied any
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The case is seen as a test of Indonesia's resolve to roll back
years of corruption and push ahead with democratic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Marzuki Darusman has said that he intends bring
the former autocrat before a judge before Aug. 10.
</P>
<P>
   President Abdurrahman Wahid has called for Suharto to be
prosecuted, although he has offered a pardon if his predecessor
returns any ill-gotten gains.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
