<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DNA tests exonerate two men accused in Newark rape  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - The investigation into the rapes of two
girls at the public library here in 1998 has been reopened after
DNA tests exonerated two men arrested for the crimes, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin Diaz was arrested on June 19, 1998, after one victim - a
16-year-old girl - identified him from a book of mug shots. Last
month, a DNA test of semen taken from the victim found that Diaz
was not the rapist.
</P>
<P>
   A DNA test administered at the same time also exonerated Jason
Yantin, who was charged with raping another woman at the library
about a month earlier, and showed that one man was responsible for
both sexual assaults. The 15-year-old victim in that case also
chose Yantin's photo from a book of mug shots.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a rush to judgment,'' Joseph Rotella, Diaz's lawyer,
told The Star-Ledger of Newark for Thursday's editions. ''My
client's name was spread all over as a sexual predator. Meanwhile,
nobody was looking for the real rapist.''
</P>
<P>
   The Essex County Prosecutors Office took a DNA sample from Diaz
only after Rotella requested it. When prosecutors decided to test
Yantin at the same time, the public defender representing him
objected. The tests were administered after prosecutors obtained a
court order to have Yantin's blood taken.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lawyers are often skeptical about what DNA evidence might
show,'' said Alan Zegas, past chairman of the criminal law section
of the New Jersey State Bar Association. ''They might not be sure
their client is telling the truth. So they oppose it.''
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts told the newspaper that the exoneration of the two
men, who had been free on bail since shortly after their arrests,
is among only a few cases in New Jersey in which DNA evidence has
cleared a defendant - and the only one they knew of in which
defendants were cleared before trial.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-year-old was raped in the second-floor restroom of the
main library in Newark on May 12, 1998. On June 17, 1998, the
16-year-old was raped in the stacks after the assailant asked for
help finding a book.
</P>
<P>
   Newark Police Director Joseph Santiago, who had publicly labeled
Diaz a ''sexual predator'' at the time of his arrest, told the
newspaper that police were obligated to arrest the men because of
the victims' identifications.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz, had been charged - but not convicted - of sexually
assaulting a former girlfriend. He had been allowed to enter a
program for first-time offenders that does not require an admission
of guilt. Santiago said he made the earlier comments about Diaz
because of the combination of his record and the new charges.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are glad to see the DNA tests exonerated them,'' Santiago
said. ''We would hate to see them prosecuted for something they
didn't do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
