<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 02:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Six Arrested in Hong Kong Fire  </HEADLINE>
By DIRK BEVERIDGE
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- Six people have been arrested in connection
with a fiery explosion set off by mainland Chinese migrants at Hong
Kong's immigration headquarters, police said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Seven people of the 50 injured were listed in critical condition
Thursday, the government said.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's political leader, Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa,
visited victims in the hospital Wednesday night and called the fire
''brutal behavior, irrational behavior that is unacceptable to all
of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said Thursday they had arrested six people and were
questioning them in a case being investigated as arson. But
immigration officials accused the migrants of a deliberate and
dangerous attack on officers who process residency claims.
</P>
<P>
   ''They set the liquid on fire and intended to injure the
officers,'' said Sunny Ho, a spokesman for the immigration
department.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration from mainland China has been the most difficult
issue to confront Hong Kong since it reverted from British to
Chinese sovereignty three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But although there have been legal battles and protests by
mainland Chinese migrants demanding the right to stay, the normally
peaceful territory had seen nothing like Wednesday's attack.
</P>
<P>
   A group of about 20 migrants went to immigration headquarters
around midafternoon, demanding documentation that would let them
stay as residents. When workers told them to leave four hours later
as the office was closing, some of the mainlanders doused the floor
with flammable liquid and set off an explosion and blaze.
</P>
<P>
   Many immigration employees returning to work Thursday seemed
fearful despite tighter security.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney who represents migrants, Pam Baker, expressed
concern the incident and comments like Tung's could turn Hong Kong
citizens against the migrants.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a small number of people out of the thousands who have
behaved with great dignity,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hong Kong government has fought to limit the number of
mainlanders who can move into the affluent territory, fearful that
its educational and social systems could be overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's highest court granted residency rights to anyone
with at least one Hong Kong parent, but the Hong Kong government
last year persuaded the Chinese central government to intervene.
Beijing declared the court had ruled wrongly, and ordered a legal
interpretation that sharply cut the number of eligible migrants.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hong Kong is now part of China, strict border controls
remain in place, keeping out numerous mainland residents who
believe they could have a better life in the former British colony,
which maintains some freedoms and capitalist ways.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 0242 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
