<HEADLINE> Marine Convicted of Rape in Japan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- A 19-year-old Marine has been convicted of raping a
woman on Japan's southern island of Okinawa and sentenced to four
years in prison, a military official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. military court sentenced Pfc. Derrick L. Oliver on
Wednesday. It also handed him a dishonorable discharge, stripped
him of all pay and allowances and demoted him to the rank of
private, Marine Corps spokesman Capt. Joseph M. Plenzler said.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, from Farmville, Va., was convicted of the March 4 rape
of a Japanese woman at his home near Futenma Marine Corps Air
Station, where he worked as a mechanic. He had pleaded innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Okinawa, 480 miles southwest of Tokyo, is home to 26,000 of the
47,000 U.S. forces stationed in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   On July 3, another 19-year-old Marine was charged with walking
into an apartment in Okinawa City in the middle of the night and
fondling a 14-year-old girl as she slept. That sparked protests on
the island, prompting President Clinton to express regret for
misconduct by U.S. service members.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to reduce growing tensions, the Marines plan to
move the Futenma air station's heliport to a less crowded part of
Okinawa.
</P>
</TEXT>
