<HEADLINE> Fiji Military Kills Rebel Supporter  </HEADLINE>
By ROHAN SULLIVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- The military intensified its crackdown on the
lawlessness that has followed Fiji's May coup, shooting one rebel
supporter to death Thursday and arresting 37 others.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 troops were sent to Vanua Levu, the country's second
largest island, to bolster the military's presence in villages that
are rebel strongholds and bases for attacks on Fijians of Indian
ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers gunned down a rebel after he shot at them with a
small-caliber hunting rifle at Dekreti village, military spokesman
Maj. Howard Politini told FM96 radio.
</P>
<P>
   Troops arrested 37 other men in the area Thursday, including
five who shot and wounded a cane farmer, Politini said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are prepared to use force if we need to, we have shown
that,'' Politini said.
</P>
<P>
   Raids, hostage-taking, theft, beatings and arson have become
commonplace in small ethnic Indian-dominated rural communities
across Fiji since the coup, which paralyzed the tourism- and sugar
export-dependent economy and sparked international condemnation of
the South Pacific nation's abandonment of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   In Suva, the last of almost 400 rebels supporters arrested by
soldiers in a tear gas raid last week were charged with unlawful
assembly and released on bail.
</P>
<P>
   The hearings clear the way for coup leader George Speight and a
group of key advisers to appear in court Saturday, prosecutors
said.
</P>
<P>
   Speight led a group of gunmen into Parliament on May 19,
claiming that ethnic Indian Fijians have too much power and
threaten indigenous Fijian culture. He held dozens of officials for
two months until the military met rebel demands for an amnesty,
agreed to discard the multiracial constitution and oust the ethnic
Indian-led government.
</P>
<P>
   Speight was arrested last week and faces minor charges as well
as a treason investigation for allegedly threatening the life of
President Ratu Josefa Iloilo after his amnesty period expired.
</P>
<P>
   The military has said an amnesty it agreed to offer Speight and
his rebels could be scrapped because they did not stick to one of
its conditions -- to turn in all their weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The crackdown comes as a new government sworn in last week has
begun day-to-day operations. On Thursday it ordered ministers in
the former Cabinet to clear out their former offices by the end of
the month.
</P>
<P>
   New Prime Minister Laisenia Qarase has promised to appoint a
commission to rewrite the constitution to strengthen indigenous
Fijians' hold on power before elections are held, possibly in three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the military's broad concessions to rebel demands,
Speight had threatened a new campaign of civil unrest unless the
new Cabinet was stacked with his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   For security reasons, prosecutors are believed to be considering
taking a magistrate to the prison island off Suva where Speight is
held, rather than bringing him to court in downtown Suva.
</P>
<P>
   In court Thursday, a Speight supporter was charged with unlawful
possession of a firearm for allegedly threatening police officers
at a roadblock May 20, FM96 radio reported.
</P>
<P>
   The charge was significant because May 20 falls within the
period covered by the amnesty, possibly indicating that prosecutors
will ignore the amnesty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
