<HEADLINE> Taliban Advances in Afghanistan  </HEADLINE>
By AMIR SHAH
<TEXT>
<P>
   KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) -- Afghanistan's ruling Taliban militia
smashed through the defense lines of opposition forces and advanced
toward a town in the northern province of Takhar, Taliban and
opposition officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban reached the outskirts of Ishkamish, 130 miles north
of the capital Kabul, Mohammed Abil, spokesman of the anti-Taliban
alliance, told The Associated Press by telephone from the
war-battered area.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy artillery was booming outside the town, and most of
Ishkamish's 40,000 people had fled, Abil said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our forces could not hold against the Taliban assault
overnight and retreated after two hours of fighting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mullah Mohammed Khaksar, the Taliban deputy interior minister,
said Taliban forces attacked Ishkamish to counter an opposition
offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ''The opposition fighters attacked us first,'' Khaksar said.
''We launched a counterattack, and our forces are now in
Ishkamish.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the opposition and the Taliban refused to give casualty
figures.
</P>
<P>
   There was also heavy fighting Thursday in Keshendeh district of
Balkh province, 170 miles northwest of Kabul, opposition spokesman
Ustad Atta Mohammed said. Both sides were using heavy artillery and
tanks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban, who rule 90 percent of Afghanistan including Kabul,
are attempting to capture the entire country. The opposition
controls the remaining 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban are Sunni Muslims and mostly Pashtun, Afghanistan's
majority ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition comprises ethnic and religious minorities,
including Shiite Muslims, Hazaras, Tajiks and Uzbeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
