<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 10:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kashmir Guerrillas, India Talk  </HEADLINE>
By QAISER MIRZA
<TEXT>
<P>
   SRINAGAR, India (AP) -- Kashmir's main Islamic guerrilla group
held unprecedented talks with India on Thursday, vowing to
implement a long-term cease-fire in the bloodstained Himalayan
province a day after a wave of shootings left 102 people dead.
</P>
<P>
   Indian Home Secretary Kamal Pande sat down for the talks with a
former separatist leader and four commanders of the Hezb-ul
Mujahedeen guerrilla group, the biggest of the groups fighting
against Indian control in Kashmir. It was the first known meeting
between the government and the guerrillas since 1989, when
militants began their war to either make the Indian-controlled part
of Kashmir independent or to merge it with Islamic Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Pande said the two sides had set up a committee to
hash out the details of the cease-fire, which the Hezb-ul
Mujahedeen declared on July 24.
</P>
<P>
   A guerrilla commander wearing a handkerchief over his face said
his group is serious about the cease-fire. Indian authorities
blamed Tuesday and Wednesday's killings in Kashmir not on the
Hezb-ul Mujahedeen, but on smaller guerrilla groups that want the
Hezb-ul Mujahedeen to keep fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will ask our six commanders to implement the cease-fire on
the ground effectively,'' said the masked commander, who serves as
the deputy chief of operations for the Hezb-ul Mujahedeen and goes
by only one name, Masood. ''We express our gratitude to the
government of India for extending an unconditional dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, there were signs that the cease-fire could be
short-lived: Sayed Salahuddin, the Hezb-ul Mujahedeen chief,
threatened Thursday to resume fighting in five days if India does
not begin joint talks with Pakistan and the militants over the
future of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   The valley has been divided between archrivals India and
Pakistan since 1948, and both sides lay claim to the entire
territory. Two of their three wars in the last half-century have
been fought over Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have given India an ultimatum that it should accept our
demand by Tuesday, 5 p.m.,'' Salahuddin told The Associated Press
in Islamabad, the Pakistani capital. ''If India doesn't initiate
meaningful tripartite talks, we will resume our operations.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 25,000 people have been killed since Indian military
and Kashmiri guerrilla forces began fighting 11 years ago.
Thursday's talks came on the heels of the most recent bloodshed: In
a series of attacks, suspected Islamic guerrillas mowed down Hindu
pilgrims and shot people in their homes around the province,
leaving 102 people dead and many more injured.
</P>
<P>
   Indian officials quickly blamed Pakistan-based guerrillas for
the deaths, saying they were reprisals for India's attempt to
secure peace in the territory. But witnesses said some of those
killed were shot by Indian forces, and Pakistan said such killings
have been carried out in the past by Indian paramilitary groups.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee arrived
in Kashmir to visit Pahalgam, the site of the worst of the
massacres. At least 35 people died and dozens were badly hurt
Tuesday when suspected guerrillas opened fire on Hindu pilgrims and
others near a religious shrine and Indian security forces fired
back.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Vajpayee told Parliament the massacre would not
deter the government from talks with the Hezb-ul Mujahedeen and
reiterated that security forces would halt all operations against
the pro-Pakistan group. India decided on both those moves toward
peace after the Hez-ul Mujahedeen announced the cease-fire last
month.
</P>
<P>
   The talks Thursday were held at the Nehru Guest House in
Srinagar, the summer capital of Jammu-Kashmir state. After the
105-minute meeting, Pande, the Indian home secretary, told
reporters: ''It was a very positive dialogue. Very cordial.''
</P>
<P>
   Masood, the guerrilla commander, said his group identified a
12-point agenda for discussion with India, including a cease-fire
and human rights violations in the province. He said his group
wanted Pakistan to be included in the talks ''at a later stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Pande countered that the talks now were focusing only on the
cease-fire. ''Pakistan will not be involved in these talks,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan has said it supports the cause of the militants but
denies it gives them cash, arms or training, as India alleges.
Pakistan's military ruler, Gen. Pervez Musharraf, on Wednesday
repeated his offer to open talks with India on the Kashmir dispute
and said the cease-fire presented an opportunity for peace.
</P>
<P>
   In a Wednesday phone conversation with President Clinton,
Vajpayee said there was no basis for a meaningful dialogue with
Pakistan because every peace initiative of his had met with
Pakistani-sponsored terrorist acts. But he added that India would
pursue the peace process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
