<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavs Detain four Foreigners  </HEADLINE>
By DANILO BURZAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The Yugoslav army said Thursday it
had detained four armed foreigners -- two Britons and two Canadians
-- suspected of training pro-Western forces in Montenegro to commit
''terrorist actions.''
</P>
<P>
   An army statement faxed to The Associated Press said the four
were arrested near the border between Montenegro and the Serbian
province of Kosovo sometime during the night between Monday and
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The four were armed ''with military equipment, explosives,
etc.,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are indications that the arrested foreigners were
training special units of Montenegrin police and that they are
specialists for explosives and terrorist actions,'' the statement
said. It said the army has ''enough material to prove the true
intentions and aims of the arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro is Serbia's junior partner in the two-republic
Yugoslav federation. Serbian authorities, who are at odds with the
pro-Western Montenegrin government, have recently alleged that
special British forces and other foreign experts were training
Montenegrin police in preparation for its secession from
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The identities of the four could not immediately be confirmed,
but there were indications that two might be employees of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe and two might
be aid workers.
</P>
<P>
   In Vienna, Austria, OSCE spokesman Mans Nyberg said two Britons
who work as instructors at the OSCE-run Kosovo police academy in
Vucitrn had been missing since Tuesday. He said they were believed
to have been with two Canadian aid workers.
</P>
<P>
   The independent Montena-fax news agency had said earlier that
the four were tourists caught with arms in their possession. But
Yugoslav army spokesman Col. Slobodan Stojanovic said the four were
''not tourists, but terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Illegal material was found in their possession for which
criminal charges are earmarked,'' Stojanovic told The Associated
Press.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest comes amid increased tensions in pro-independence
Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   There are fears that trouble may erupt in the republic ahead of
Sept. 24 Yugoslav elections, which the Montenegrin leadership has
vowed to boycott. Leaders here also worry that the Yugoslav army --
which is under the control of autocratic Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic -- may try to oust the Montenegrin government,
which has a smaller but well-trained and well-equipped paramilitary
police force.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling Montenegrin Democratic Party of Socialists said that
by claiming foreign instructors are training Montenegrin troops,
Milosevic and his allies are trying to ''prepare ground for a
physical assault on Montenegro ... and the elimination of its
democratic leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Yugoslav authorities -- who have been increasing their
anti-Western propaganda ahead of the elections -- announced that
four Dutchmen were arrested in Yugoslavia in July for allegedly
plotting to assassinate Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests follow allegations that NATO has hired mercenaries
to snatch fugitive war crimes suspects on Yugoslav territory,
tightening the noose around indicted Serb leaders. Yugoslav
authorities claimed the Dutch were on a mission to kill or abduct
Milosevic or former Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic and bring
them to the U.N. war crimes tribunal in The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch government has demanded access to the detainees in
accordance with international conventions, Foreign Ministry
spokesman Bart Jochems said Thursday. But he said a Yugoslav
official in The Hague would not give details of the charges, where
the Dutch detainees were being held or their medical condition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 1104 </TRAILER>
