<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 11:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Police Free Bombing Suspect  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUESSELDORF, Germany (AP) -- As a wave of neo-Nazi activity
continued, police on Thursday freed a former German soldier
questioned in a bomb attack that injured immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   The 34-year-old man owns a military shop near the commuter train
station in Duesseldorf where a World War II hand grenade was
detonated last week, injuring 10 immigrants from the former Soviet
Union, six of them Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   ''It turned out not to be a hot lead,'' state prosecutor
Johannes Mocken said. While the suspect had a police record, he had
not been linked to the right-wing scene, Mocken said.
</P>
<P>
   Police refused to speculate about the motive for the attack. But
the fact that all the victims were foreigners has raised fears that
it was carried out by far-right extremists. The victims were all on
their way to catch trains home after leaving their daily German
class.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation continues amid a series of racist attacks that
have prompted calls from politicians including Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder for authorities and the public to do more to stem a rise
in extremist violence.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, police reported several fresh cases of right-wing
activity, including two new incidents in North Rhine-Westphalia,
the region which includes Duesseldorf.
</P>
<P>
   In Kaldenkirchen, police said they detained three skinheads for
following asylum-seekers and threatening them with clubs and iron
bars.
</P>
<P>
   In Essen, police were seeking those responsible for throwing a
fist-sized rock through the bedroom window of the home of a
Moroccan family Wednesday night. A note attached to the rock
featured a swastika and Nazi slogans, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, five youths attacked a man from India, hitting him on
the head, on a train from Leipzig in eastern Germany late
Wednesday, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, police in the eastern town of Eisenach arrested
10 youths for shouting slogans including the Nazi ''Sieg Heil!''
salute. Two African asylum-seekers were attacked and chased through
the same town last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities also reported vandalism, including an overturned
grave, at the former Woebbelin concentration camp. Police said it
was the third time the site had been vandalized in recent weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
