<HEADLINE> Suharto Charged With Corruption  </HEADLINE>
By GEOFF SPENCER
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Two years after student protests and
riots forced him from office, former President Suharto was charged
Thursday with siphoning $570 million from state coffers.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said they may take the 79-year-old former autocratic
leader to court within days. His lawyers maintain he is too ill for
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto, who is under house arrest at his Jakarta home, received
a visit from authorities and signed a document acknowledging he had
been formally charged, said Yushar Yahya, a spokesman for the
attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   The former president, who ruled Indonesia for 32 years, was
referred to only as ''the defendant'' in the legal papers.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has been formally charged. This will be followed with us
filing the indictment and a dossier on the case in court,'' said
Umbu Laga Lazore, a member of a state investigative team that
painstakingly probed Suharto's wealth over the past eight months.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors formally assumed responsibility for the case against
Suharto on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Marzuki Darusman has said he intends to bring
Suharto before a judge sometime before Aug. 10. If convicted, he
could face life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto is accused of using charities under his control to
siphon as much as $570 million in state funds to bankroll business
empires for his family and cronies.
</P>
<P>
   Some estimates put the wealth of Suharto's relatives at $40
billion -- a figure his family denies. They also say there is no
Suharto family fortune stashed abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto has denied any wrongdoing. One of his lawyers, Mohamad
Assegaf, said Suharto fully cooperated with the officials Thursday
and said he understood that they were ''only doing their duty.''
</P>
<P>
   President Abdurrahman Wahid has offered to pardon Suharto if the
stolen money is surrendered. Despite the offer, the case holds
immense symbolic importance as a test of Indonesia's resolve to
fight corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers raised doubts a hearing would start soon because
of their client's health. His family and attorneys claim a series
of strokes has impaired his speech and ability to remember
financial transactions and other details.
</P>
<P>
   One Suharto physician, Dr. Hari Sabardi, cautioned against
forcing the ex-leader into a courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not sure if he will be able to understand questions put
to him and be able give the right answers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Darusman, a human rights activist during Suharto's reign, said
Suharto must face trial, and cited recent independent medical tests
that declared the former leader fit enough to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto's rule ended May 21, 1998, following protests against
his rule and rioting in the capital, Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, hundreds of police were deployed near Suharto's
home and blocked a peaceful protest by several hundred students.
They want him tried immediately, not only for corruption but also
for human rights violations carried out by Indonesia's military
under Suharto's orders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
