<HEADLINE> Youth Games delayed by transportation troubles  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CHARLOTTE AMALIE, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) - A tournament for
youth athletes from five U.S. cities began one day late Thursday
because of transportation problems at the site in the U.S. Virgin
Islands.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Youth Games, scheduled to begin Wednesday, were delayed
because of a dispute between organizers and a private bus company
over the cost of transporting the students, said the event's acting
president, Orville Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament on the island of St. Croix features 600 athletes
from Birmingham, Ala.; Columbia, S.C.; Washington D.C.; Newark,
N.J., and Boston, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Some delegations missed the opening ceremony on Tuesday because
they lacked transportation, Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers hired the government-owned bus service, Vitran, at
the last minute, but on Wednesday the buses brought some students
to the wrong site, Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most of the delegations were understanding about what we were
going through,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Volleyball and basketball games were pushed back a day. Other
events - such as golf, swimming and bowling - were set to begin
Thursday, with track and field scheduled for Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
