<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Snakes Rescued Before Fete  </HEADLINE>
By RAMOLA TALWAR BADAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOMBAY, India (AP) -- Hundreds of snakes, their mouths sewn shut
and venom glands punctured, were confiscated by wildlife officials
Thursday on the eve of a Hindu festival in which starving cobras
and rock pythons are forced to drink milk.
</P>
<P>
   Some 50,000 snakes die every year during the Nagpanchami
festival, when people offer milk, butter and sweetened rice to
starving snakes, according to India's World Wide Fund for Nature.
</P>
<P>
   Days before the festival, snake handlers puncture venom glands,
pull out fangs and sew the snakes' mouths shut so they will be
harmless and hungry for the special food, which they do not
normally eat, the fund said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''The mouths of the snakes are stitched and punctured by iron
rods so that the snake does not bite. These wounds turn septic and
the snakes often just starve to death,'' said Kedar Gore, an
education officer at the conservation group.
</P>
<P>
   ''Snakes never drink milk, but they are force-fed. They then
either have diarrhea or the milk goes into the lungs and they choke
to death,'' Gore said. The snakes usually die within a few days
after the festival and the snake handlers sell their skins on the
black market.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past couple of years, teams of wildlife officials and
volunteers have been swooping down on snake charmers who display
snakes outside railway stations and temples. The snake charmers
encourage passers-by to throw money or place milk near the snakes
during the days leading up to the festival.
</P>
<P>
   Protests by wildlife enthusiasts and awareness campaigns in
schools and colleges have drastically curtailed the number of snake
charmers who arrive in Bombay before the festival.
</P>
<P>
   Snakes are held as sacred in India and clay idols of snakes are
commonly seen in temples. Snake charmers face from six months to
two years in prison for violating the Wildlife Protection Act, but
are generally let go after a day in police custody.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 1458 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000803.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court: State can decline to collect taxes from Indians  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The Pataki administration can legally refuse
to collect taxes on motor fuel and cigarettes sold by Indian
vendors to non-Indian customers, an appeals court decided Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous ruling by the five-member Appellate Division of
state Supreme Court panel in Albany rejected arguments by
non-Indian retailers who have been seeking for years to get the
state to tax their Indian counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   The non-Indian businessmen argue that by not charging state
sales taxes on reservation purchases of tobacco and gasoline to
non-Indian customers, the state is putting them at a huge
competitive disadvantage with those Indian-run businesses.
</P>
<P>
   With the state's tobacco tax nearly doubling to $1.11 a pack
starting on March 1, Indian vendors not charging sales taxes can
now sell a carton of cigarettes for $13.50 less than vendors who
collect state taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Under a July 1998 state Court of Appeals ruling, the state
Department of Taxation and Finance's refusal to collect the sales
taxes from Indian vendors was defensible if it could be proven that
the agency has a ''rational basis'' for not doing so.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate division decided Thursday that there is such a
rational basis.
</P>
<P>
   ''The record here clearly ... makes plain that the statutes
cannot effectively be enforced without the cooperation of the
Indian tribes,'' Justice D. Bruce Crew III wrote for the court.
''Because of tribal immunity, the retailers cannot be sued for
their failure to collect the taxes in question, and state auditors
cannot go on reservations to examine the retailers' records.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the court said the Pataki administration's attempts
in 1997 to seize shipments of gasoline and tobacco products on
which state taxes had not been paid ''resulted in civil unrest,
personal injuries and significant interference with public
transportation on the state highways.''
</P>
<P>
   ''In our view, all of these factors provide a rational basis for
the differential treatment of the parties,'' Crew said.
</P>
<P>
   The administration in 1998 issued new regulations superseding
the old ones requiring the collection of taxes from Indian vendors
and said the new non-collection policy would be permanent.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the group which was the lead plaintiff in the case,
Jim Calvin of the New York Association of Convenience Stores, said
Thursday's ruling will be appealed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would ask the average New Yorker to ask this question: Is it
rational to allow certain people to ignore the tax law simply
because they threaten violence?'' Calvin said. ''And is it rational
to require some retailers to file tax reports, collect and remit
tax receipts (to the state), withstand tax audits and be exposed to
tax penalties, while totally exempting other retailers from those
same requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   Calvin said state legislators have decreed that Indian vendors
should pay the tax on tobacco and gas sales to non-Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ''The executive branch chose to enforce that law selectively,''
Calvin said. ''Now we have the judicial branch saying it is OK for
the executive branch to enforce that law selectively. That's
scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Indians believe their reservations are sovereign nations and
that their vendors doing business on Indian land are not subject to
New York state taxation.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Crangle, a Buffalo lawyer who filed a friend-of-the-court
brief in the case on behalf of Mohawk and Seneca merchants, said
the unanimous ruling may represent the end of the case. Since the
state's highest court, the Court of Appeals, has already heard the
matter and sent it back down to the lower court for further
proceedings, it would be hard for non-Indian businesses to get the
Court of Appeals to hear it again, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Crangle also said Thursday's ruling was a victory for Indian
tribes because it extends to Indian retailers the principle that
they have sovereign immunity from being sued over the
non-collection of taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ''This certainly demonstrates that the state policy that
Governor Pataki initiated recognizing sovereign immunity is now
being confirmed by the courts,'' Crangle said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Convenience Stores and M.W.S.
Enterprises, a Buffalo-area business, joined Calvin's group in
challenging the Pataki administration tax enforcement policy.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Taxation and Finance had no immediate
comment on Thursday's ruling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-03-00 1527 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
