<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High-Tech Worries Send Stocks Lower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose Thursday, erasing earlier losses as
bargain hunters successfully pulled the market out of a slump in
technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 49.45 at 10,736.98.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, down as much as 137.21 in early
trading, was up 40.82 at 3,699.28. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
was up 9.12 at 1,447.82.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of recently beaten down stocks fell back into favor,
helping to lift the broader markets. Oracle was up $3.75 at $76.875
and Cisco System up $3.625 at $64.563.
</P>
<P>
   On the Dow, bellwether gainers Thursday included General
Electric, up $1.25 at $53, and J.P. Morgan, up $3.25 to $135.25.
</P>
<P>
   Investors sold technology stocks early in the session, extending
that sectors' recent losses following a string of mediocre
second-quarter earnings reports from some high-profile companies.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, several companies have warned that earnings will
probably fall off in the second half of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The latest concerns about technology earnings arose when Lehman
Brothers reported that Motorola was telling suppliers it was seeing
lower demand for handsets. That put pressure on the entire wireless
phone group. Motorola was down 56.30 cents to $36.25, while Nokia
slipped $1 to $40.25.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, semiconductor equipment maker Kulicke &AMP; Soffa
Industries Inc. warned that earnings later this year could fall
below forecasts. Kulicke fell $5.625 to $16.50.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq has fallen more than 14 percent in the past two weeks
amid worries about slowing earnings growth at technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are still lots of concerns in the tech and telecom
sectors,'' said Ronald Hill, investment strategist at Brown
Brothers Harriman &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said the Dow was drawing some support from health care,
consumer non-durables, utilities and food and beverage stocks-- all
which tend to fare better in a slowing economy.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest gauge on inflation, orders to American factories
shot up by 5.5 percent in June, the biggest increase in nine years.
While the report suggests strong economic growth, the figure met
analyst forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few weeks, investors have tried to sort through
mixed signals about the economy, and whether or not it is slowing.
The economy's direction is critical to determine whether the
Federal Reserve will further tighten credit when its policymakers
meet Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 830.10 million
shares, ahead of Wednesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 8.65 at 496.09.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
