<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Actor's Release Sought  </HEADLINE>
By K.N. ARUN
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRAS, India (AP) -- Bells chimed in Hindu temples where fans
prayed Thursday for a film star abducted by a ruthless gang, and a
newspaper editor trekked into a forest to try to negotiate his
release.
</P>
<P>
   Actor Rajkumar and three companions were seized Sunday from the
film star's vacation home by a gang led by a notorious outlaw,
Veerappan, who has eluded police for years.
</P>
<P>
   On a tape Veerappan handed to the actor's wife, he demanded the
release of a man being held without charge and warned against
harming any Tamils.
</P>
<P>
   R.R. Gopal, editor of the magazine Nakeeran, trekked 270 miles
to the fringes of the Andhiyur-Satyamangalam forest range but was
forced to stop when heavy rains lashed the area, said police chief
F.C. Sharma of southern Tamil Nadu state.
</P>
<P>
   Gopal, the only journalist who has ever interviewed Veerappan,
plans to try to establish contact with him in the 4,000-square-mile
forest. He is traveling with two correspondents and a cameraman.
</P>
<P>
   Gopal was acting on behalf of the governments of neighboring
Karnataka and Tamil Nadu states. He has interviewed Veerappan three
times, each time traveling to the outskirts of the forest, where he
was then blindfolded and forced to walk for three days before
meeting the outlaw.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Rajkumar's admirers have attended prayer services in
dozens of Hindu temples since the actor's abduction.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the top elected official in Karnataka state, Chief
Minister S.M. Krishna, traveled 180 miles by helicopter to the
mountaintop Malai Mahadeshwara temple Thursday for prayers, joined
by his wife, Cabinet members and the actor's son.
</P>
<P>
   Veerappan, 56, who has eluded capture for 18 years, has ruled
the forest for 30 years, killing at least 130 policemen,
slaughtering elephants and felling sandalwood trees, police say.
</P>
<P>
   He apparently suffers from asthma and has repeatedly offered to
surrender in exchange for amnesty. The government of Karnataka,
where most of his crimes occurred, wants to put him on trial for
his crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Rajkumar, 72, has appeared in more than 200 Kannada-language
films over five decades and is politically powerful in Karnataka
state. Like many people in southern India, Rajkumar and Veerappan
go by only one name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 1548 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000803.0111 </DOCNO>
