<DOCNO> APW20000803.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Keep Concorde Flight Ban  </HEADLINE>
By CLAR NI CHONGHAILE
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- The French Transportation Ministry decided Thursday
to keep the ban on Concorde flights until experts clarify exactly
what caused an Air France supersonic jet to crash, killing 113
people.
</P>
<P>
   The top aide to Transportation Minister Jean-Claude Gayssot,
Gilles Ricono, told reporters the technical investigation into the
July 25 crash was going quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ''But, today, uncertainties still surround the interpretation
and the sequence of events, and it is not yet possible to answer
decisive questions necessary before resuming flights,'' he said.
''The suspension of the Concorde flights cannot, in these
conditions, be lifted today.''
</P>
<P>
   Air France has five Concordes. British Airways, which has seven
Concordes, resumed its flights a day after the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Ricono spoke after aviation experts met at the Transportation
Ministry to try to determine what new safety measures are required
before Air France Concordes can take off again.
</P>
<P>
   The Concorde crash killed all 109 people on board and four
people on the ground. The jet, spewing flames and smoke, slammed
into a hotel outside Paris shortly after takeoff from Charles de
Gaulle airport.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Ministry's Accident and Inquiry Office, which
is investigating the crash, expects to deliver its preliminary
report at the end of August.
</P>
<P>
   The Accident and Inquiry Office has said that flames seen
spewing from the side of the aircraft before it crashed most likely
came from a major fuel leak. It has also said one or two of the
jet's tires exploded, one of the engines shut down, and another
failed twice -- once during takeoff and again about one minute
later.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say they have not determined how all these
elements worked together to turn the Concorde into a flying bomb.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Accident and Inquiry Office said Thursday that
pieces of a water deflector -- a shield used to reduce spray into
the engines from tires on wet runways -- was found on the runway
where the Concorde started its fatal journey.
</P>
<P>
   ''We found pieces of a deflector, but from the beginning that
has not been a secret,'' Paul-Louis Arslanian said. ''It is an
element of the inquiry, it is not the inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   He was responding to questions prompted by a report in the
newspaper USA Today that quoted unidentified sources as saying
investigators are trying to determine whether a piece of the jet's
landing gear broke off before takeoff, leading to a fuel leak.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper said investigators found a water deflector on the
runway, and that a water deflector on a British Airways Concorde
caused a fuel leak in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   An official British report on that incident said it was almost
certain that energy released from a burst tire broke the deflector
and hurled debris against the underside of the wing, causing a
puncture and releasing fuel.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways said it modified the design on its Concordes
afterward, fitting the deflector to the landing gear more securely.
Air France said Thursday it had not carried out the modification
because it was not mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   French authorities have set up a special investigation unit to
establish legal responsibility and potential liability for the
crash. Named Concorde 95, the unit includes 44 members of the
French national police and three judicial experts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 1615 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000803.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wife of accused killer to be allowed to testify in old murder case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYLVAN BEACH, N.Y. (AP) - The wife of a man charged in the death
of a 12-year-old boy 22 years ago will be allowed to testify in the
case, a judge has decided.
</P>
<P>
   Oneida County Court Judge Michael L. Dwyer issued his decision
earlier this week to allow certain statements from the wife of
Arthur Mills.
</P>
<P>
   Mills is accused of pushing Raymond Umber Jr. into the water at
the Sylvan Beach pier on Oneida Lake in July 1978. Umber hit his
head as he fell in to the water, and Mills, who was 17 at the time,
did nothing to help him, prosecutors claim.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're happy and we agree with this ruling,'' Assistant
District Attorney Scott McNamara said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials ruled the death an accidental drowning at the time.
But in March, Mills, now 39, was charged with second-degree murder
in the boy's death after witnesses came forward with new
information and state police re-opened the case.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Umber's body was exhumed to allow a forensic
pathologist a chance to determine the exact cause of death.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is scheduled to begin Sept. 11. Defense attorney
Joseph Lupia is trying to get a change of venue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-03-00 1616 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000803.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungarian WWII Prisoner May Return  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) -- A Hungarian who was apparently captured
in World War II and spent 53 years in a Russian mental hospital may
be brought to Hungary this month, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman, Gabor Horvath, told Hungarian state television
that the Russian government is willing to repatriate the man, known
as Andras Andreyevich Tamas.
</P>
<P>
   It will take about two weeks to complete the paperwork and issue
him a Hungarian passport, Horvath said. The state airline Malev has
offered to fly the man home.
</P>
<P>
   The patient was transferred from a prison camp to a mental
hospital in Kotelnich, 600 miles east of Moscow, in 1947. Since he
could not speak Russian, the man was forgotten until a Slovak
doctor recognized his speech as Hungarian.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Andras Veer director of Hungary's National Psychiatric and
Neurological Institute, visited him last week and determined he was
an ethnic Hungarian, perhaps from an area that is now in Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
   Horvath said no record of the man's birth nor any living
relatives had been found so far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 1626 </TRAILER>
