<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Founder of New Covenant leaves charter school's board of trustees  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The founder of the state's largest charter
school has resigned from its board in the wake of a state report
alleging he mishandled school funds.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Dare, who founded the New Covenant Charter School in
Albany in 1999 and led it through a troubled first year, stepped
down from the school's board of trustees Wednesday, a little over a
month after he resigned as board chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Dare told an Albany newspaper his resignation was not related to
release of the report.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, made available Wednesday by the State
University of New York's Charter School Institute, Dare wrote a
check, using New Covenant funds, for $89,000 to Milton Horne, owner
of Milton Horne Inc., for construction work done at the school's
temporary facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction came two days after Dare received $442,800 from
the Albany City School District and deposited it to a bank account
opened in the name of the school.
</P>
<P>
   But the report said Milton Horne Inc. had been hired by The
Commons LLC, which leased the modular classrooms to New Covenant.
The Commons is a for-profit subsidiary of the Urban League of
Northeastern New York, which sponsored New Covenant's charter. Dare
serves as the Urban League's president. The report said the payment
to Horne should have come from The Commons, not from the school.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 3, Dare transferred $353,800 of the school district's
money to Advantage Schools Inc., New Covenant's management company
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Advantage dated that same day, Dare said the
remaining $89,000 of the original $442,800 from the Albany City
School District had been spent on rental fees, energy costs and
accounting fees. But the report concluded that no such payments
were made with the $89,000 from the school district.
</P>
<P>
   New Covenant's money should have first gone through The Commons
or directly to Advantage, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Dare explained that he had written the letter in late January
with the intention of making the payments with the $89,000. But he
said The Commons' payment to Milton Horne was long overdue and that
''the school's very existence'' was threatened by the debt, the
report quoted Dare as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The Commons has since begun reimbursing New Covenant for the
payment made to Milton Horne, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The state report was prepared by Glens Falls lawyer Richard
Bartlett, a former dean of Albany Law School and one-time state
assemblyman who was appointed by the Charter School Institute to
look into New Covenant's management. The institute approved New
Covenant's charter.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is our recommendation ... that Aaron Dare remove himself
from the board of trustees of the school or that he be removed,''
the report concluded. ''Mr. Dare cannot serve as the chief
executive of Urban League and Commons and continue to sit as a
trustee of the school without continuing to create conflicts of
interest, real or perceived.
</P>
<P>
   The Charter School Institute sent the report on Friday to New
Covenant along with a letter citing various violations found during
an end-of-the-school-year review.
</P>
<P>
   Dare told the Times Union newspaper of Albany that his
resignation was not prompted by the report and that he wants to
spend more time with his family and on the Urban League.
</P>
<P>
   Dare's resignation coincided with Eleanor Bartlett's taking over
as the school's new director. A member of the state Board of
Regents, Bartlett is no relation to lawyer Richard Bartlett.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Ricciardi, an attorney representing New Covenant, said
the school is ''still sorting out the facts'' but the ''board's
feelings are that Aaron has done nothing wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He did not misuse the school funds, for himself or for the
Urban League,'' Ricciardi said. ''It might have been better if the
payment was made through The Commons, but in the end it was state
money used for the school.''
</P>
<P>
   New Covenant is the first of the state's five charter schools
currently in operation. During its first year of operation, it was
plagued by disciplinary problems and poor academic performance. It
has switched management companies from the Boston-based Advantage
to the Manhattan-based Edison Schools Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Charter schools are taxpayer-funded but operate with an
independent charter, or license and with less restrictions than
regular public schools. They are designed to provide parents with
an option in areas where they feel the public schools are lacking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
