<BODY>
<HEADLINE> After visit, man writes $1 million check for small city library  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   GLENS FALLS, N.Y. - Millionaire amusement park pioneer Charles
R. Wood hadn't set foot in his local library in 20 or 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   But at the urging of Crandall Public Library Trustee Judy Dee
and his friend, Josie Beckos, Wood agreed to pay a visit recently.
</P>
<P>
   He ended up paying much more.
</P>
<P>
   He said that what he saw there amazed him. So after two more
visits, he donated $1 million to the library's $10 million
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ''Older people were reading papers over here and youngsters were
milling around reading books and working on computers,'' Wood said
Wednesday as he presented the check to library officials. ''It was
like their home away from home.''
</P>
<P>
   The expansion proposal for the library 50 miles north of Albany
still needs to be approved by local voters in November.
</P>
<P>
   Wood requires that the money be used for children's resources.
He spent a lifetime operating nearby amusement parks called the
Great Escape and Gaslight Village and a camp for sick children
called the Double H Hole in the Woods Ranch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
