<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bar Association: Lawyers are not so bad after all  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Lawyers aren't such bad people after all,
the state Bar Association reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers' group said attorney disciplinary statistics from
1999 in New York state showed that more than 99 percent of the
112,000 lawyers in the state were not disciplined for misconduct
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-six lawyers were disbarred by courts for professional
misconduct in 1999, 106 were suspended, 24 were censured and 26
lawyers resigned from the practice of law while facing disciplinary
action, according to the Bar Association's committee on
professional discipline.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that only 242 lawyers were disciplined shows that the
''popular opinion'' of lawyers being involved in ''chicanery'' or
as ''hired guns willing to do anything for a fee'' is untrue, the
bar association said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We continue to see the development of an effective
professional discipline system as a constructive and progressive
means of regulating the practice of law,'' said Brooklyn lawyer
Barry Kamins, head of the bar's professional discipline committee.
''We want the public, media and the profession, to understand that
discipline agencies are for real and take their jobs very
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   The most common infractions which earned lawyers disbarment or
other disciplinary actions last year was the misappropriation of
clients' funds, tax evasion, ''client neglect'' and other behavior
which reflected badly on the practice of law, the bar association
said.
</P>
<P>
   The number of complaints filed against lawyers dropped from more
than 16,000 in 1998 to just over 15,000 in 1999. Kamins attributed
the decline to the effects of continuing legal education and ethics
courses for lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Geographically, the Bar Association said 35 lawyers were
disbarred, 40 were suspended and eight were censured in the state
judiciary's First Department (encompassing Manhattan and the
Bronx); 41 lawyers were removed, 43 suspended and six censured in
the Second Department (New York City except for Manhattan and the
Bronx, plus Long Island and five counties north of New York City);
seven lawyers were disbarred, 17 suspended and four censured in the
Third Department (28 counties in eastern and central New York); and
three lawyers were removed, six suspended and six censured in the
Fourth Department (western and northern New York).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-03-00 1648 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000803.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
