<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court says county sheriff's fee is an illegal tax  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - He's no real estate broker, he's the county
sheriff. And that means the Hudson County sheriff can't collect
more than $30,000 in commission on a land deal.
</P>
<P>
   The commission on a property sold before a court-ordered auction
was excessive and amounted to an illegal tax on the sale, a state
appeals court ruled Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Hudson County Sheriff's Department thought it was in line
for a legally allowed slice of the $3.8 million deal. According to
court papers, the department spent less than $1,000 to handle the
transaction.
</P>
<P>
   ''The sheriff is a constitutional officer and public official.
He or she is not a private sector salesman or a broker entitled to
a contractual commission, no matter what the costs may be,'' Judge
Edwin H. Stern wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The case began after two parties agreed on the sale of a
property that had been earmarked for a sheriff's sale.
</P>
<P>
   The buyer balked at paying the commission required by state law.
By following state statutes, the county's cut came to $30,408.64.
If the property sold at auction for the same price, the commission
would have been doubled.
</P>
<P>
   A trial court judge called the state law that allows the
commission unconstitutional. The appeals court did not. In this
case, they said the amount was inappropriate, not the law that
requires it.
</P>
<P>
   ''We merely hold,'' Stern wrote, ''that there is no evidence the
Legislature intended to put the disproportionate burden of taxation
on a limited number of users of the sheriff's services.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling and its impact on other counties and other proposed
sales is being examined, said Stephen E. Trimboli, a lawyer for the
Sheriff's Association of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not clear whether this decision is limited to the facts
of this case or not,'' Trimboli said.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson County Sheriff Joseph T. Cassidy did not return a message
left at his office.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Hudson County executive's office said the
decision is under review by the county's legal staff.
</P>
<P>
   ''The strength of the dissent will likely lead to an appeal to
the state Supreme Court,'' Julie St. Jean said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-03-00 1710 </TRAILER>
