<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Officials Said to Rap Film  </HEADLINE>
By ALI AKBAR DAREINI
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- Iranian officials have summoned the film
director husband of pop star Googoosh to court over a film they say
violates the Islamic dress code, a newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Googoosh and her husband, Masood Kimiai, said the
move was an attack by hardliners on the increasing cultural
freedoms associated with moderate President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
   The summons against Kimiai was issued after the Revolutionary
Guards, who see themselves as the upholders of the Islamic
revolution, filed a complaint over Kimiai's film ''Protest.'' They
said the film was ''promoting inadequate Islamic dress code,'' the
government-owned daily newspaper, Iran, reported.
</P>
<P>
   Kimiai and Googoosh are abroad shooting a film. On Saturday,
Googoosh performed in Toronto for 12,000 people, her first concert
since Iran's 1979 Islamic revolution halted her career. The
goverment bans women from singing or dancing before audiences that
include men.
</P>
<P>
   Googoosh's songs, stunning looks and flashy Western outfits made
her a star in pre-revolutionary Iran. Despite a ban, her music
still outsells that of any other Iranian artist and is widely
available on bootleg tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Googoosh, 50, was allowed to leave Iran to perform but it is not
clear whether she will be allowed to return. If she does, she is
certain to face hardliners' wrath.
</P>
<P>
   Kimiai's film, which criticizes social restrictions in today's
Iran, is attracting thousands of viewers every day, many of them
young people opposed to the restrictions imposed by the religious
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Iran's social laws have eased since Khatami's 1997 election, but
hardliners vigorously oppose attempts to ease restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ''The film 'Protest' promotes the wrong culture of the former
regime as well as inadequate Islamic dress code. The film sets a
wrong model for Iranian youth,'' the Iran newspaper quoted the
complaint as saying.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't say when the summons was issued and there was no
immediate comment from the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   Mojdeh Akrami, a 29-year-old woman, saw the movie and said it
contained nothing shocking. ''This film was no different from other
recent Iranian movies I've seen and there was no violation of the
Islamic dress code. I think political considerations were behind
the summoning,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This appears to be a deliberate complaint to create a new
challenge to cultural reforms,'' well-known Iranian actor Jahangir
Almasi told The Associated Press. ''Summoning, boycotting and
detention will not help political and cultural maturity in our
society.''
</P>
<P>
   
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 1710 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000803.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Appeals court rules that Trump apartment building in UN area is legal </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The 72-story apartment tower that Donald Trump
is building near the United Nations over the objections of Walter
Cronkite and other area residents is legal, a Manhattan appeals
court ruled Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Appellate Division of State Supreme Court, upholding a lower
court decision, ruled 4-0 that the residential edifice at 845 First
Ave., between 47th and 48th Streets, complies with zoning
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   A triumphant Trump called the appeals court ruling ''a great
victory'' and said ''I'm very happy about it.'' He said those who
opposed the tower were ''a bunch of rich people who lost their
views'' of the East River.
</P>
<P>
   The developer said the building, 856 feet high, will be the
tallest residential tower in the world and people will start moving
in as early as January. He said the building's apartments are about
75 percent sold.
</P>
<P>
   Cronkite and other members of the opposition group complained
that Trump's building, which will be some 300 feet taller than the
39-story U.N. building, will dwarf the headquarters of the world
body.
</P>
<P>
   Peter L. Zimroth, lawyer for the opposing coalition, said he
will seek permission to appeal to the state's highest court within
the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Zimroth had argued to the Appellate Division that zoning laws
clearly bar buildings such as Trump's from that area. He said the
building sits in two different commercial zones, neither of which
permits that type of tower.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Lindenbaum, the lawyer who got the Buildings Department
and the Board of Standards and Appeals to approve Trump's tower,
said both zones are designated R-10, the highest residential
density allowed.
</P>
<P>
   As long as a building is primarily residential, Lindenbaum said,
it matters little what the underlying commercial zones and rules
are. The building must comply with residential zoning rules.
</P>
<P>
   In his decision in December, Justice Nicholas Figueroa said the
zoning law language was somewhat ambiguous and that he would defer
to the experts as long as their interpretation of the law has a
rational basis.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal court upheld Figueroa's decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-03-00 1722 </TRAILER>
