<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> City, mall developer sue over legal challenges by rival  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) - The legal tug-of-war over the Long Wharf
Galleria got more intense Thursday, when the city and the mall
developer filed an antitrust lawsuit against a rival mall company
that's been accused of trying to kill the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit in Superior Court accuses Westfield America Inc. and
affiliates of the Australia-based developer of violating the state
Unfair Trade Practices Act in an effort to keep its regional mall
monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Westfield has also filed frivolous lawsuits, multiple Freedom of
Information Act requests and complaints with government agencies to
delay and ultimately kill the planned development, the lawsuit
claims.
</P>
<P>
   The city and Long Wharf Galleria LLC also sued the city of
Milford for working with Westfield to undermine the Long Wharf
development to protect the Connecticut Post Mall, eight miles away
in Milford.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fair competition is encouraged, promoted and protected in this
country. Unfair competition, anticompetitive conduct, monopolistic
behavior is prohibited by law,'' said Steven Fischman, president of
New England Development, a developer of the mall.
</P>
<P>
   Westfield in turn attacked this lawsuit as ''frivolous.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an act of desperation by a mayor who has pushed a very
unpopular project,'' Westfield attorney Ronald Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks unspecified triple damages and a halt to
frivolous lawsuits. No date for a hearing has been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor John DeStefano said the city is losing $150,000 in taxes
each week the project is delayed, plus lost permit fees and
thousands of jobs and wages for city residents. He said the mall
would have been well on its way to being built by now if it were
not for Westfield's legal delays.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have faced a calculated, methodical strategy from Westfield
to stop New Haven from building its future ... and it has caused us
severe financial harm,'' DeStefano said.
</P>
<P>
   The $500 million mall would be built on 55 acres near the
intersections of Interstates 91 and 95.
</P>
<P>
   New England Development said it has secured commitments from
Nordstrom, Macy's, Filene's and Lord &AMP; Taylor to be anchor tenants,
and the company plans to put about 150 other stores in the shopping
center.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the state reaffirmed its pledge of $28 million in aid
for the project and declared that the mall would pose ''no
significant impact'' to traffic, the environment or to area
retailers - a claim mall opponents say is absurd.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe if the project is scrutinized the way the law
requires the project to be, any rational person looking at adding
millions of car trips to I-95 and I-91 would not approve it,''
Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen added that Westfield is not the only retailer that would
be hurt by the mall. Downtown shops in New Haven and other area
towns, as well as strip malls and other local businesses, would
lose customers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Public support for this mall would exist if it were a good
idea,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, however, accuses Westfield of playing both sides of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Westfield was one of 10 developers that responded to the
original request for proposals for the mall development in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   After New England Development and Fusco Inc., a New Haven
developer, were chosen for the project, Westfield did a study of
the impact the mall would have on its malls in Milford and Meriden.
</P>
<P>
   The report concluded that about 45 percent of sales at the new
mall would be diverted from the Meriden and Milford malls, which
would see $100 million less in annual sales, the lawsuit claims.
</P>
<P>
   The company's other Connecticut malls are in Enfield and
Trumbull.
</P>
<P>
   Westfield has offered to redevelop downtown New Haven if the
mall project is stopped, and has asked tenants for the new mall to
withdraw in favor of other deals at its malls, the lawsuit alleges.
</P>
<P>
   DeStefano said the city of Milford has been a ''co-conspirator''
in the anti-mall effort.
</P>
<P>
   But Milford Mayor Fred Lisman said he is surprised that his city
was sued.
</P>
<P>
   Milford had sued New Haven and the mall developers to have
another hearing before the regional planning agency that initially
approved the project. A judge threw out that lawsuit, which
Westfield funded, but Milford is appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ''We sued because we wanted free discourse and truth, and we're
being sued for asking for that,'' Lisman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-03-00 1725 </TRAILER>
