<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton questions Lazio vote on lobster aid  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHPORT, N.Y. (AP) - Hillary Rodham Clinton on Thursday
questioned Rep. Rick Lazio's vote against a bill that included aid
for Long Island's lobster fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio campaign said the congressman had fought to include $8
million for lobstermen in the emergency spending bill, but that in
the end he voted against it because it ballooned into a ''$13
billion Christmas tree'' that ''included all sorts of pork which
jeopardized the fiscal health of the country. ... He was
disappointed the bill turned into what it did,'' said Lazio
spokesman Bryan Flood.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed the House in March but was never acted on in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ''If anybody should have been a strong advocate for getting that
money immediately to our lobsterman and getting the money needed to
look at the causes of the dying off of the lobsters, it should have
been somebody who represents Long Island,'' Clinton said as she
stood in a park on Scudder Beach overlooking Long Island Sound in
Northport.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio later sponsored the Long Island Sound Restoration Act,
which provides nearly $14 million in aid for fishermen hard-hit by
a mysterious die-off of lobsters, especially in the western part of
the sound.
</P>
<P>
   ''His Long Island Sound Restoration Act will go a long way to
ensuring that our lobsterman are protected,'' Flood said.
</P>
<P>
   Lobstermen in Connecticut and New York each are slated to get
$3.6 million in direct aid. The bill also provides $6.6 million for
research into the cause of the die-off.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's work on cleaning up the Sound and his votes against
strip-mining have earned him strong praise from environmental
advocacy groups like Friends of the Earth and the League of
Conservation Voters.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio spent lunchtime in Brooklyn, eating at a kosher pizzeria
in Borough Park and introducing himself to voters - most of them
Orthodox Jews.
</P>
<P>
   In an impromptu sidewalk press conference, he expanded on
comments he made when asked about abortion on ''The O'Reilly
Factor,'' a Fox News show. Asked when he believes life begins, he
had told the show: ''You have a very special moment when you have
conception.''
</P>
<P>
   He added Thursday: ''I don't know precisely when life begins.
It's a religious and deeply spiritual question. I know what the law
respects and what I support and that is the standard of Roe v. Wade
in terms of viability.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to name his favorite Supreme Court justice, he said Sandra
Day O'Connor. O'Connor has joined with more liberal justices on the
high court in upholding abortion rights in recent votes.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio also said on ''The O'Reilly Factor'' that he voted against
same-sex marriages because ''I just believe in respecting
traditional marriages. ... Just in terms of marriages, it's a
biological fact, you know? It's how society replicates itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the passers-by who met Lazio outside the kosher pizza
place were unsure who he was, but voter Rivka Rabinowitz's reaction
was typical: ''Anybody running against Hillary's got my vote. I
can't tolerate her. She's a liar and a very big anti-Semite.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was accused in a recent book, ''State of a Union,'' of
having made an anti-Semitic remark in an argument in 1974. She has
denied the allegation. Some conservative Jews also believe she is
too sympathetic to the Palestinians, despite her recent statements
that U.S. aid to the Palestinians should be cut off if they declare
statehood unilaterally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-03-00 1726 </TRAILER>
