<HEADLINE> Business news in brief from around New Jersey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) - Comprehensive Medical Diagnostics Group
said Thursday it has acquired CAT-EEG, a leader in telemedicine and
cardiac testing.
</P>
<P>
   CAT-EEG, of Lynbrook, N.Y., was founded in 1969. It serves
physicians, hospitals and nursing homes by providing mobile
diagnostic services for their patients, as well as portable heart
and other monitors that can send the health-care provider medical
data via telephone after a patient has chest pain, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Comprehensive, formed last month from the merger of
Comprehensive Medical Group and American Risk Management Group,
provides administrative support services to small and medium-sized
businesses, and medical diagnostic and telemedicine services to
health care clients. Last month, it acquired Cardiovascular
Laboratories, which performs non-invasive diagnostic tests such as
ultrasound and echocardiography in hospitals and doctors' offices.
</P>
<P>
   The new company is negotiating other acquisitions of companies
that provide different diagnostic services as it moves further into
medical services, according to newly appointed president James
Clingham.
</P>
<P>
   CEDAR KNOLLS, N.J. (AP) - AlphaNet Solutions Inc., a major
information technology services firm, said Thursday it has been
awarded a $200,000 contract to build a secure computer network
infrastructure for On-Line Investment Services Inc.
</P>
<P>
   On-Line gives investors the ability to day-trade securities
through high-tech trading systems at competitive prices.
</P>
<P>
   AlphaNet will re-engineer or replace infrastructures such as
switches, routers and firewalls for On-Line's network at its Jersey
City headquarters, and will provide one-site support services at
On-Line's growing network of branch offices.
</P>
<P>
   AlphaNet specializes in network design, operations, management
and security, and also offers remote network management, call
center support and other services.
</P>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) - Spalding Sports Worldwide has been
named the first official licensee of the XFL, a new professional
football league.
</P>
<P>
   Under the multiyear license agreement announced Thursday,
Spalding will serve as the official league ball and will market a
line of footballs under the XFL name. The balls will be used in all
games, beginning with the season opener on Feb. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Spalding plans to begin selling its new football line in
October. It will also launch a multimillion dollar XFL advertising
and promotional campaign this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The league is jointly owned and operated by World Wrestling
Federation Entertainment Inc. and NBC.
</P>
<P>
   PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) - RCN Corporation expects to begin offering
its high-capacity, fiber optic network in Brooklyn by early 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the company's Megaband Network is under way in
Brooklyn and the Bronx. Customers in the Bronx should have access
sometime after Brooklyn service is available.
</P>
<P>
   RCN has mapped out, designed or built more than 7,864 miles of
its network in the New York-New Jersey area.
</P>
<P>
   The new network allows RCN to deliver current services while
using only 15 percent of the network's capacity. The remaining 85
percent will be available for new services offered in the future.
RCN currently offers local and long distance phone services, cable
television and high-speed Internet access.
</P>
</TEXT>
