<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CDC testing six New Jerseyans for possible exposure to West Nile virus </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - State officials have referred six suspected
cases of the West Nile virus to the Centers for Disease Control
after finding the people displayed several symptoms of the disease
or came from counties where dead crows were found infected with the
virus.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials tested about 50 New Jerseyans suspected of
having a human West Nile virus last year, but none tested positive.
The mosquito-borne virus killed seven people in New York City last
year and sickened dozens.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, more than two dozen people have received screening
tests for St. Louis encephalitis, a strain of the West Nile virus,
in New Jersey, said state Department of Health and Senior Services
spokesman Dennis McGowan. All the tests came back negative, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The state referred six cases to the CDC based on two criteria:
Either a person who complained of illness had a fever of over 100
degrees, muscle weakness, disorientation, and signs of infection in
spinal fluid, or the person met some of these categories and came
from a county where dead crows have been infected with the virus,
McGowan said.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen dead crows have been found to be infected with West Nile
this year - 10 in Bergen County, two in Middlesex, two in Union and
one in Hudson County. No mosquitoes or ''sentinel'' chickens being
tracked by the state have tested positive for the virus
</P>
<P>
   McGowan would not specify which counties the six people came
from or how old they are, saying state officials didn't want to
unnecessarily alarm a particular region or age group. Elderly
people, children under age 5 and people with weak immune systems
are believed to be more susceptible to the virus, which can cause
only flulike symptoms in healthy people.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of the people, an elderly man with several other
medical problems, is from Bergen County, said Tom Ammirato, a
spokesman for Bergen County Executive William ''Pat'' Schuber. The
man was treated at a hospital in New York City, Ammirato said.
</P>
<P>
   Results from the CDC are expected next week, McGowan said.
</P>
<P>
   State hospitals have been told to refer any cases of patients
displaying West Nile symptoms to the Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   Several patients have been referred who likely have viral
meningitis, an illness with many of the same symptoms, said Steven
Sperber, an infectious disease specialist at Hackensack University
Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   The virus is difficult to diagnose because it has a short
incubation period and is similar to many other ailments, he said.
Many people infected with the virus are not symptomatic at all or
have only a slight fever, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sperber said he expected many patients to flood hospitals in
coming weeks, concerned that their flulike symptoms may be
something greater.
</P>
<P>
   ''Last year, the outbreak started right around this time,'' said
Sperber.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Department of Health and Senior Services:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.state.nj.us/health/cd/westnile/enceph.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
