<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Toys R Us online operation sued over privacy concerns  </HEADLINE>
By CONNIE MABIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN (AP) - In separate class-action lawsuits, two women have
sued Toysrus.com and accused the online toy store of illegally
providing personal information about shoppers to another company.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits were filed Wednesday in U.S. District Court in
Austin on behalf of Hawaii resident Leah Benbow and Florida
resident Lisa Laufman.
</P>
<P>
   The women claim that their personal information was transmitted
without permission from what they thought was a secure Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The women sued the Web site, parent company Toys ''R'' Us Inc.
of Paramus, N.J., and software maker Coremetrics for at least
$10,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco-based Coremetrics, which has offices in Austin,
offers a program that helps retailers track the browsing and buying
patterns of Internet customers. The software can track how
customers reach a site, such as whether they are lured by an
advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   Toysrus.com is a Coremetrics client.
</P>
<P>
   Toys ''R'' Us spokeswoman Rebecca Caruso said the company has
not seen the two Austin lawsuits but is aware of two similar claims
filed Wednesday in New Jersey and California. She would not comment
on specifics of the lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't sell or rent visitor information to other parties,''
she said. ''Our customers' personal business and privacy are very
important to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Coremetrics issued a statement saying it will fight the
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ''The lawsuit is based upon a complete misunderstanding of the
services Coremetrics provides. We believe the cases have no merit
and intend to vigorously defend ourselves in these litigations,''
the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Toysrus.com's posted privacy statement doesn't mention
Coremetrics by name, but the toy seller says it reserves the right
to gather information about its shoppers and share it with
advertisers and other companies. Such information doesn't identify
individuals, the policy says.
</P>
<P>
   The women seek $10,000 or $100 for each day the information was
allegedly transmitted to Coremetrics - whichever is larger. They
also seek the $1,000-per-person relief asked for each person who
joins the class-action lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Messages left with both women's lawyers Thursday were not
immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.toysrus.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.coremetrics.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-03-00 1806 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000803.0148 </DOCNO>
