<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Airman to be buried near mother 56 years after crash  </HEADLINE>
By TIM MOLLOY
<TEXT>
<P>
   A long-lost airman who died when a B-24 crashed into a mountain
in China in 1944 is to be buried alongside his mother on Saturday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   The casket holding the remains of Anthony DeLucia was delivered
Wednesday to his hometown of Bradford, about 80 miles south of
Buffalo, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel better that if I'm ever in this situation my family
would be the beneficiaries of the Army really going out of its way
to being their own home,'' said Army Capt. Paul Gonthier, who is
counseling DeLucia's family throughout the remains' return.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even though this gentleman is from a long time ago, he's still
one of our brothers,'' Gonthier said.
</P>
<P>
   Two farmers found the crash site while searching for rare herbs
on 7,000-foot Kitten Mountain in Guangxi Province in 1996. The
remains of DeLucia, a flight engineer, and nine others on the
bomber were recently examined at the Defense Department's forensic
laboratory in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   One of the airmen was buried last month in Kingston, N.Y.; the
rest will be buried soon in Arlington National Cemetery in
Arlington, Va. or in private funerals. The names of the crewmen
also will be placed on a tombstone at Arlington National Cemetery
on August 21.
</P>
<P>
   DeLucia's brother, Elmer, flew to Hawaii last week to escort the
casket home. He had promised their mother, Jennie, to bury him in
the family plot in north-central Pennsylvania if he were found.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, who died in 1968, never truly believed that her son
had died during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ''They had always thought the plane had crashed into the
ocean,'' said Vince Gaeto, a friend of the family and the funeral
director handling DeLucia's burial. ''His mother always said,
'Well, he was a good swimmer.'''
</P>
<P>
   Elmer DeLucia recently met David Rankin, one of the
investigators who sought the remains at the crash site. About 80
people were involved in the three-year search. In July, the Army
gave Elmer DeLucia his brother's dog tags.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral Mass is scheduled for 10 a.m. Saturday at the St.
Bernard Roman Catholic Church in Bradford, with burial to follow at
St. Bernard Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen servicemen will attend to carry the flag, perform a
21-gun salute and serve as pallbearers. DeLucia's family will
receive his Purple Heart.
</P>
<P>
   The plane crashed on Aug. 31, 1944 - Anthony DeLucia's 24th
birthday - as it returned from a bombing raid near Formosa, now
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Another brother, Augie, was wounded during World War II when the
plane he was piloting was shot down over Stuttgart, Germany. Elmer
DeLucia was part of a mortar company in the D-Day landing in
Normandy. Both brothers provided blood samples for DNA tests in the
effort to identify Anthony DeLucia's remains.
</P>
<P>
   Gaeto, a veteran himself, said he was surprised at how much work
the Army did to return the remains.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just phenomenal that the U.S. government, without batting
an eye, was willing to do this and was willing to bring these men
home,'' Gaeto said. ''It gave me tremendous pride and faith in our
government.''
</P>
<P>
   The other airmen on the bomber were identified as 1st Lt. George
H. Pierpont of Salem, Va.; 2nd Lt. Franklin A. Tomenendale of
Shabbona, Ill., 2nd Lt. Robert L. Deming of Seattle, Wash., 2nd Lt.
George A. Ward of Jersey City, N.J., Sgt. Ellsworth V. Kelley of
Newark, Ohio; Pfc. Charles Buckley of Garden City, Kansas, Staff
Sgt. William A. Drager of Washington, N.J., Sgt. Robert L. Kearsey
of McKees Rocks, Pa.; and Private Vincent J. Netherwood of
Kingston, N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-03-00 1807 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000803.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Navy Buys $18 Million Supercomputer  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Maritime accidents like the one in the movie
''The Perfect Storm'' may be easier to prevent with a new
supercomputer just bought by the Pentagon, IBM says.
</P>
<P>
   International Business Machines Corp. announced Thursday that
the $18 million computer, code-named ''Blue Wave,'' has been
installed at the Naval Oceanographic Office computer center at
Mississippi's Stennis Space Center.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Adamec, the center's director, said the ability of the IBM
RS/6000 SP to do modeling and simulation will help in the designing
of aircraft and ships and will create models of the ocean's waves,
currents and temperature to forecast weather patterns better.
</P>
<P>
   IBM said the computer is the most powerful supercomputer ever
bought by the Defense Department, the fourth-fastest supercomputer
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ''The RS/6000 SP extends NAVOCEANO's ability to solve the
Department of Defense's most difficult computer problems,'' Peter
Ungaro, an IBM vice president, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Computers are ranked on a standardized speed test that measures
how many calculations they perform in a second. This one was judged
the fourth most powerful in early June by groups at the University
of Tennessee and the University of Mannheim in Germany, which
publish the rankings twice a year. Used in conjunction with other
equipment at the Navy center, the computer will perform 3 trillion
operations per second, IBM said.
</P>
<P>
   The three ranked faster were Intel's ASCI Red at Sandi National
Laboratory in New Mexico; IBM's ASCI Blue Pacific, Lawrence
Livermore National Laboratory, Calif.; and SGI's ASCI Blue Mountain
at Los Alamos Laboratory in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   But the list is likely to be revised at the next ranking, and
the new computer dropped to fifth place, since IBM announced in
late June that it had built the most powerful supercomputer in the
world, able to perform 12.3 trillion operations per second.
</P>
<P>
   That one is to be used by the U.S. Energy Department at the
Lawrence Livermore lab.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Naval Oceanographic Office:
http://www.navo.navy.mil/newpage/index4.htm
</P>
<P>
   Department of Energy: http://www.doe.gov
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory: http://www.llnl.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 1808 </TRAILER>
