<HEADLINE> Russian Media Empire Denies Sale  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- The independent media company Media-Most on
Thursday denied that it might be sold to the state-controlled
natural gas monopoly, Gazprom.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of a sale emerged when the deputy chief of the presidential
administration, Vladislav Surkov, was quoted by the New York Times
on Thursday as saying that the Media-Most holding may be sold to
Gazprom for debts.
</P>
<P>
   Media-Most, owned by oligarch Vladimir Gusinsky, called the
statement a ''lie'' and said it was part of Kremlin attempt to
influence negotiations with Gazprom and to disrupt the work of its
media outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Media-Most confirmed it was holding talks with Gazprom on
possibly handing over some of its stock as payment for a loan, but
insisted that control over the media company will not change hands.
</P>
<P>
   A Gazprom spokesman would not give details of the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Gazprom owns about 30 percent of Media-Most's NTV television
channel and holds 17-20 percent more of NTV's stock as collateral
for a loan. Gazprom has been stepping up pressure on NTV in recent
months to settle its debts.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Media-Most accused the Kremlin of trying to
silence the reporting of its news outlets, which have been critical
of President Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Media-Most had been accused of defrauding the government in a
privatization deal, and its owner, Gusinsky, was jailed for four
days in June in a case that some observers regarded as punishment
for Media-Most's criticism of the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   The charges were dropped last week for lack of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Gusinsky stemmed from the privatization of
the St. Petersburg television company ''Russian Video,'' whose
head, Dmitri Rozhdestvensky, has been jailed since 1998 awaiting
trial on charges of misappropriating state funds.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a St. Petersburg court ruled that Rozhdestvensky
can be released from custody upon his pledge that he will not leave
the city, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
