<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sonics' First-Round Pick Signs Deal  </HEADLINE>
By MIA PENTA
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- First-round draft pick Desmond Mason signed a
three-year contract with the Seattle SuperSonics.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's unbelievable,'' the 6-foot-5 guard said Thursday at a
news conference. ''It's a dream come true for me.''
</P>
<P>
   As the 17th overall pick, Mason was eligible under the rookie
salary scale to sign a three-year contract worth $3.47 million. The
Sonics will have an option for a fourth year at $1.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Mason, who played four seasons at Oklahoma State, said he was
challenged by his stint in the rookie Shaw Pro Summer League 2000
run by the Boston Celtics. The Sonics and nine other NBA teams
participated.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a step up,'' he said. ''I learned a lot of defensive
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Paul Westphal and Sonics president and general manager
Wally Walker said they were pleased with Mason's performance in the
summer league.
</P>
<P>
   He was awarded the first Shaw Cup, to be given annually to the
fledgling league's outstanding player.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't know they were even giving out this award,'' Mason
said. ''It was a big thing for me, and my family was happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason averaged 18.0 points and 6.6 rebounds in his final year at
Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal said he wasn't sure where Mason would fit in with the
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   He will be given a chance at shooting guard -- starter Brent
Barry's position -- but Westphal said Mason's defensive skills,
versatility and ability to shoot well from the outside are likely
to guarantee him court time this season.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's as ready as any rookie to play,'' Westphal said. ''He
plays with great effort and has a good knowledge of the game. It's
hard to imagine him not playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics are trying to shed the image of an older team by
acquiring aggressive youngsters like Mason and Rashard Lewis, the
forward who re-upped for three years Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal said he's optimistic about the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sure we'll be better than last year,'' he said. ''The West
keeps getting tougher and tougher but we have taken steps to move
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason said he is happy to be in Seattle and will work to meet
the standards of his idols Gary Payton, Horace Grant and Vin Baker.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to play hard every day,'' he said. ''That's all I
can do. That is all they can ask for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
