<HEADLINE> Miss America brings message to Vietnam veterans' convention  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - She's a slight woman with a southern drawl,
a beauty queen who prefers to carry her crown in a box.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the veterans she meets have been in wheelchairs longer
than she's been alive, but when Miss America speaks, they listen -
whether she's pushing hepatitis C screening or poking fun at
military rivalries.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Heather French brought her work on behalf of
veterans to the Vietnam Veterans of America's National Leadership
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're the reason why I became Miss America,'' she told
several hundred members, many of whom would later vie for hugs and
handshakes.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of a Marine veteran wounded in Vietnam, French has
made homeless veterans her cause and has testified several times
before Congress about their plight.
</P>
<P>
   She promised to carry on the work after her reign, when she
becomes the ''second lady of Kentucky.'' She is to marry that
state's Lt. Gov. Steve Henry Oct. 27.
</P>
<P>
   ''This passion isn't something you can turn on and off like a
light switch,'' she said. ''I will always be the daughter of a
disabled Vietnam veteran. I will always be affected by his trauma
and his troubles.''
</P>
<P>
   French, 25, has used her celebrity to raise awareness of
hepatitis C. Spread through blood-to-blood contact, the potentially
deadly inflammation of the liver afflicts veterans in higher
numbers than the general public.
</P>
<P>
   ''In Vietnam alone there were over 365,000 blood transfusions in
a two-year period,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   With symptoms sometimes taking 30 years to appear, many Vietnam
veterans are only now starting to feel the effects.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're starting to see a lot of these veterans with their
disabilities getting weaker and weaker and a lot of them don't know
why,'' she said. ''But we encourage them to go get tested for
hepatitis C because there is treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Veterans seem to respond, she said, when they hear the message
coming from a veteran's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ''They know there are other people out there who care about them
and want to see them lead a better future,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Jack Hertzel, president of VVA chapter 850 in Smyrna,
Del., agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''When she shows up, people show up for testing,'' he said.
''She's helped us out a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   French seldom wears her Miss America crown, saying it is a
representation of the veterans' voice, with each jewel standing for
a veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ''A gentleman in Dallas, Texas, said, 'Well if every stone
represents a veteran can I pick out mine?'
</P>
<P>
   ''Y'all are so brave,'' she deadpanned.
</P>
<P>
   ''I did tell him, however, that it seems the Marines pick the
big stones,'' she said. ''I'm not sure why.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-03-00 1834 </TRAILER>
