<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Beach closings at record lows last year  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BELMAR, N.J. (AP) - Good news, beachgoers: The number of beach
closings in New Jersey plunged to record lows last year, according
to a report released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   There were 34 ocean and bay beach closings due to pollution in
1999, down dramatically from the 194 closings that New Jersey
averaged between 1988 and 1994, according to the 10th annual
''Testing the Waters'' report issued by the Natural Resources
Defense Council.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the closings occurred at Monmouth and Ocean county
beaches, the group said. Among the reasons: polluted stormwater
discharges and sewage plant failures.
</P>
<P>
   The group said New Jersey was one of 11 states that
''comprehensively monitor'' water quality at beaches and notify the
public about the results.
</P>
<P>
   It also praised the state Department of Environmental Protection
for frequent monitoring of ocean water quality.
</P>
<P>
   ''These tough requirements are the winning formula that should
be emulated both in New Jersey and nationwide,'' said Curtis
Fisher, executive director of the New Jersey Public Interest
Research Group, which released the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
