<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two men charged in 1999 death of graduate student  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HAYS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A Brooklyn man was charged Thursday with
stabbing a graduate student in the back during a mugging last year
on a darkened Brooklyn street, taking her life for ''virtually
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The defendant, David Jamison, 27, was ordered held on a
first-degree murder charges after a prosecutor claimed he confessed
to stabbing Amy Watkins in the potential death penalty case. An
alleged accomplice charged with second-degree murder, Felix
Rodriguez, 20, also was denied bail during a separate appearance in
Brooklyn Criminal Court.
</P>
<P>
   Jamison decided to rob ''Ms. Watkins, who was in the wrong place
at the wrong time, to satisfy his need for a small amount of
money,'' prosecutor Michael Vecchione told a judge. ''She was
killed, quite frankly, for virtually nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   A large knife used by the victim's assailants ''went almost
completely through her body,'' Vecchione added.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins' father, who was in court Thursday, said he wanted a
severe prison sentence for his child's killer - not death. By law,
prosecutors have 120 days to decide whether to make pursue a
capital case once a defendant is arraigned on an indictment.
</P>
<P>
   ''The death penalty would almost be an easy way out,'' Lawrence
Watkins said. He and the victim's stepmother, Gayle Greene Watkins,
said they were struck by how young - and emotionless - the
defendants looked.
</P>
<P>
   ''These boys were the last people to see our daughter, to touch
our daughter,'' Mrs. Watkins told reporters. ''We wanted to see
something in their faces that would tell us something.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside court, an attorney for Jamison, Jonathan Sims, said he
''would vigorously challenge the authenticity of the confession,
especially how it was elicited by police.'' Both Sims and
Roderiguez's attorney, Steven Chaiken, also claimed that witnesses
had not been able to pick either men out of police lineups -
something prosecutors did not dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The slaying horrified the city and the victim's neighbors in
Prospect Heights, a quiet neighborhood of gentrified brownstones a
short subway ride from Manhattan. It came at a time when the city
was in the midst of a dramatic decrease in violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins, 26 and from Kansas, was studying for her masters in
social work, counseling battered women and working with children as
an intern at the New Settlement Community Center in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   On the evening of March 8, 1999, Watkins had taken the subway
from the Bronx, where she organized a meeting for parents about
their children's reading scores. She was attacked as she walked
home from the subway station, after stopping for some groceries
shortly before 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Jamison and two other men saw Watkins walk by the
restaurant they were in, and decided she would be an easy robbery
target. Watkins apparently struggled with her attacker and she was
stabbed once, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The victim was unconscious when passers-by found her on the
sidewalk - some residents said they had heard a woman scream. She
lived with a roommate in an apartment building about two blocks
from where she was stabbed.
</P>
<P>
   She was born in Illinois but raised in Topeka, Kan., and
graduated from the University of Kansas. She moved to New York in
1997 after living briefly in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins was a second-year graduate student at Hunter College's
School of Social Work, had an internship at the center and had
started working there in September 1998.
</P>
<P>
   She was buried in suburban St. Louis, where her mother, Margaret
Tafoya, and her stepfather, John Tafoya, live. Lawrence Watkins
teaches at Dominican Academy in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Jamison was picked up for questioning Wednesday thanks to
several tips to police, including some from the Crime Stoppers hot
line. He had previously been arrested for selling drugs, petty
larceny and robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Sims said his client had been convicted only once, for
misdemeanor drug possession in 1994. Since then, he added, Jamison
''has been on the right track,'' recently moving into a new
apartment with his wife and young daughter.
</P>
<P>
   A third man was questioned extensively from Wednesday afternoon
to Thursday morning at the 77th Precinct in Brooklyn, but was
released without any charges being filed against him, police said.
</P>
</TEXT>
