<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former CEO at sentencing: I was no 'stud stock picker'  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A former top Wall Street executive who gave
inside information on bank stocks to an X-rated movie actress was
sentenced to eight months in prison Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Kimba Wood, commenting that insider trading
''undermines investor confidence in the securities markets,'' also
imposed a $25,000 fine and ordered James McDermott Jr. to perform
300 hours of community service.
</P>
<P>
   The sentence was less than half of what federal sentencing
guidelines recommended for his April conviction for conspiracy and
securities fraud during his affair with porn star Kathryn Gannon.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said she could sentence McDermott, 49, to a lower
prison term because he was needed at his Briarcliff Manor, N.Y.,
home to care for a daughter who had extraordinary needs. She did
not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Wood noted that McDermott had been arrested twice for drunken
driving, including once in 1999, and said she saw ''one element
common to all of Mr. McDermott's crimes: a recklessness that
disregards the public interest.''
</P>
<P>
   At the sentencing, McDermott stood and turned toward more than
50 spectators as he apologized publicly ''to my wife and two
daughters.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Where I see weakness and cowardice, they saw strength and
courage,'' he said in a firm voice that had become a fixture on
television financial programs as he rose to chief executive officer
of the New York investment bank, Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods.
</P>
<P>
   He disputed prosecutors' portrayal of him as an arrogant Wall
Street big shot who broke the law despite a $4 million a year job.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was called a stud stock picker, a master of the universe,''
McDermott said. ''Those things couldn't be further from the truth.
I'm just an average person who tried to work hard and give back.''
</P>
<P>
   He lost his job and status as a leading expert on bank stocks
after he gave inside information to Gannon, a Canadian known as
''Marylin Star'' in the X-rated movie industry.
</P>
<P>
   Denis McInerney, McDermott's lawyer, asked Wood to let his
client avoid prison because of numerous acts of charity and
community service and because his crime occurred while he was
plagued by alcoholism and depression. The judge, however, noted
that he managed to perform well in his job despite those ailments.
</P>
<P>
   McInerney said McDermott had already suffered immensely from
public humiliation, being made fun of by late night talk show
comedians and having a television police show episode based on his
case.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is tortured by how hard this has been for his family,''
McInerney said, noting that friends find McDermott at times to be
barely coherent and sobbing.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said she could not excuse his conduct, ''motivated by
self interest,'' but she took McDermott's charitable actions into
consideration in reducing his sentence. The federal guideline range
is a year and nine months to two years and three months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   She also noted that he has seemed to rehabilitate himself in the
last year, avoiding alcohol. As part of his sentence, he must
participate in an alcohol aftercare treatment program and undergo
two years of probation after beginning his prison term on Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell B. Kleinman, lawyer for Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods, said
he told his wife on the telephone immediately after the sentencing
that the judge ''bought into the submissions,'' including letters
from 85 people praising McDermott as well as arguments by his
lawyers for leniency.
</P>
<P>
   ''She bought into it completely,'' Kleinman said he told his
wife, who also is a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   But Kleinman said his comments were not meant to imply that the
firm thought McDermott deserved a harsher sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not unsympathetic human beings,'' he said. ''Obviously
something strange happened in his life.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the firm has a new management team in place and remains
the second largest investment banking firm in the country in terms
of number of annual transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ''None of our clients ever really expressed to us any doubts
about us as a result of this whole situation. I feel that this
thing is largely behind us. The sentencing obviously represents a
final episode,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Gannon, 31, allegedly shared some information with Anthony
Pomponio, 45, of North Caldwell, N.J., who was convicted of insider
trading charges after acknowledging his own affair with Gannon.
Gannon and Pomponio allegedly made $170,000 in illegal profits.
</P>
<P>
   Gannon was arrested in May at her Vancouver, British Columbia,
residence and is free on $50,000 bail. She also has a home in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Extradition proceedings are underway to bring Gannon to the
United States. Pomponio's sentencing is Sept. 6.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
