<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> $Adv06  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILDWOOD, N.J. (AP) - Bless them, Father, for they are hot. And
sunburned. And dripping with perspiration, standing four deep in
the corners and elbow to elbow up in the bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   The air conditioner in the gymnasium of Wildwood Catholic High
School is noisily cranking, but it is no match for the humidity or
the body heat. More than 1,000 people - in sandals, tank tops,
cut-off jeans - have crammed themselves in here for the 11 a.m.
Sunday Mass.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Rev. Jaromir Michalak performs the sign of the
cross to start the service, people are still filing in. Some stay
squished into the corners, some climb past the basketball hoops and
into the bleachers by the championship banners that hang from the
walls.
</P>
<P>
   The late arrivals know better than to go looking for a vacancy
in the rows of wooden folding chairs that cover the hardwood floor
court.
</P>
<P>
   ''People in the summer, they're just trying to find a church on
the island,'' Michalak says later in an interview. ''They're happy
to find us here.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to summer church, seashore style.
</P>
<P>
   As surely as the beaches, boardwalks and amusement parks of the
Jersey shore fill up when the weather warms, so do the pews,
confessionals and bleachers of churches and other houses of
worship.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's nine months of worry, three months of scurry,'' said
Rabbi Aaron Krauss, of Temple Beth El Synagogue in Margate, echoing
a saying used by clergymen of all faiths from Point Pleasant Beach
to Cape May.
</P>
<P>
   The change from winter to summer is dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   On Long Beach Island, there is only one place to attend Roman
Catholic services in the offseason. It is St. Francis of Assisi in
Brant Beach, which holds five Masses every Sunbay.
</P>
<P>
   In summer, St. Francis opens mission churches in Loveladies,
Beach Haven and Surf City to accommodate the bigger congregations.
Among the four locations, the parish offers 20 Sunday Masses, each
attended by 800 to 1,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a big, big operation,'' said the Rev. Andrew Reitz,
its pastor.
</P>
<P>
   Priests are imported - from Franciscan institutions like Siena
College in Albany, N.Y., St. Bonaventure University in Olean, N.Y.,
and Washington Theological Union in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the communion hosts, the tiny wafers signifying
the body of Christ, which are served at all Masses. ''When we
order, we order 200,000 of them. And that doesn't even carry us
through the summer. We always have to order more,'' Reitz said.
</P>
<P>
   At St. Ann's Roman Catholic Church in Wildwood, one of only two
parishes serving Wildwood, North Wildwood, Wildwood Crest and West
Wildwood, the summer-to-winter dichotomy is equally dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   The 71-year-old baroque cathedral, one of the state's biggest
churches, holds 2,800 people. In winter, it has more than enough
space and there are empty seats in all six of the Sunday Masses.
</P>
<P>
   Not so in summer, when the population of the Wildwoods goes from
15,147 to an estimated 250,000. The parish adds eight Masses - five
of them held at Wildwood Catholic High School, about a mile away.
</P>
<P>
   Between 75 and 90 percent of those attending are out-of-towners,
according to the Rev. Michael P. Orsi, pastor.
</P>
<P>
   At the high school, church workers drape a blue cloth with a
white cross on it over one of the basketball backboards at one end
and erect a makeshift altar beneath it.
</P>
<P>
   It's not St. Patrick's Cathedral, but it serves the purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's part of our faith to attend Mass every Sunday, and they
make it easy for you here,'' said Fran Boyer, 50, of Oaklyn, a
regular summer visitor who attends Mass at the high school. ''My
sons always like this better (than St. Ann's). It's less formal.
They feel more comfortable, with the basketball hoops and
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Happy to see a packed house, pastors sometimes struggle to
accommodate all the extra people. On a recent Sunday, a first-time
visitor sitting in the back of St. Ann's during a 9:30 a.m. Sunday
Mass was tapped to serve as an usher, collecting money.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter that the man was a newcomer.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a pleasure,'' Orsi says of his swollen summer flock. ''I
can't tell you what a pleasure it is. It's wonderful to have a full
church. You hear so many people complain about people not going to
church anymore. Well, you tell them: They're all coming to
Wildwood,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   End Adv06
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-03-00 1846 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
