<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Civilian Rule on Comoros  </HEADLINE>
By RODRIQUE NGOWI
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORONI, Comoros (AP) -- The military ruler of the Indian Ocean
nation of Comoros said Thursday that he will not restore civilian
rule to the republic until one of the three islands halts its
attempts to secede.
</P>
<P>
   Comoros has been plagued by coups, assassinations, and military
rule since it gained independence from France in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   The island of Anjouan unilaterally declared independence in
August 1997, complaining it was not receiving its fair share of
export revenues -- mainly from the sale of ylang-ylang flowers used
in perfume and vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be no elections for a civilian administration until
unity and border integrity of the Comoros archipelago are restored
with the recovery of Anjouan,'' Col. Azali Assoumane said in an
interview with The Associated Press. He also called for
''tightening economic and communications sanctions against Anjouan
to curb ... separatist leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Organization of African Unity imposed sanctions
on Anjouan in an attempt to force the tiny island to return to
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Assoumane said he was concerned about a repeat of 1975, when
residents of Anjouan, Grande Comore and Moheli voted overwhelmingly
in favor of independence and a fourth island voted against. That
island, Mayotte, became a French overseas territory, though it is
claimed by the Comoros government.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1997, Anjouan and Moheli islands announced plans to
secede in order to gain status similar to Mayotte's, but France
refused. Government troops failed to defeat the secessionists.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1999, representatives of the three islands met under
OAU mediation. Those from Grande Comore, the archipelago's main
island, and Moheli agreed to a peace plan, but Anjouan
representatives did not.
</P>
<P>
   Following three days of rioting in Grande Comore, Assoumane --
then army chief of staff -- seized power in a bloodless coup. He
later issued a timetable that called for a return to civilian rule
by April 2000.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he said the country may take the first steps toward
restoration of ''constitutional order'' at a three-day conference
beginning Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The conference is expected to deliberate on how the Anjouan
crisis can be resolved and draft a new constitution, under which
the military ruler would relinquish some of his sweeping powers to
a prime minister and legislature. The legislature would be
appointed by a conference of political parties, the army,
professional bodies, and religious leaders.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Central Bank, Comoros' 690,000 people depend on
$24 million a year sent home by 180,000 Comorans living in France.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 1849 </TRAILER>
