<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polonia Re-Signs With Yankees  </HEADLINE>
By RONALD BLUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Luis Polonia walked into the Yankees' clubhouse
3&AMP;frac12; hours before gametime, shook a few hands and said his hellos.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm excited,'' he said. ''Who doesn't want to play for the New
York Yankees?''
</P>
<P>
   Polonia signed with the Yankees three days after the Detroit
Tigers released him. New York immediately inserted him into the
lineup, batting leadoff and playing left field against the Kansas
City Royals.
</P>
<P>
   New York manager Joe Torre said Polonia could see time in left,
at designated hitter and as a pinch-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ''I told Luis yesterday on the phone,'' Torre said, ''we'll do
it as we go along.''
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old outfielder hit .273 with six homers in 80 games
for Detroit with a .325 on-base percentage. Detroit put Polonia on
unconditional release waivers Monday to make room for Triple-A
prospect Billy McMillon. Polonia maintains he was let go so that a
2001 option in his contract wouldn't become guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I always thought it would be nice to go back to New York
before I retired,'' said Polonia, joining the Yankees for the third
time. ''I didn't think it would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Polonia loved playing for the Yankees and owner George
Steinbrenner so much that when New York and the Tigers agreed in
June on a tentative trade that would have sent Juan Gonzalez to the
Yankees, he lobbied the two-time AL MVP to go. Gonzalez ultimately
used his no-trade clause to block the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ''I told Juan, 'Don't think about it. You want to go. You want a
ring, right?''' Polonia recalled.
</P>
<P>
   He told Gonzalez not to worry about the money now, saying that
if Gonzalez performed well, ''George will take care of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes Juan has too many people to make his decisions,''
Polonia said.
</P>
<P>
   Polonia played with the Yankees during parts of the 1989 and
1990 seasons, then was traded to Anaheim. He returned as a free
agent in December 1993, and New York traded him to Atlanta in
August 1995 following the return of Darryl Strawberry.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the talk Thursday was of an at-bat he had against the
Yankees, playing for the Braves in the 1996 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   With the Series tied 2-all and New York ahead 1-0 in the ninth
inning of Game 5, Polonia pinch-hit against John Wetteland with two
outs in the bottom of the ninth and runners on first and third.
</P>
<P>
   Polonia fouled off six straight fastballs, then sent a shot into
the gap in right-center that looked like a game-winner -- before
Paul O'Neill caught the ball on the run near the warning track for
the final out.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew I was going to get a fastball,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Polonia thought he had fouled off 9-12 pitches. Did he think he
had the winning hit?
</P>
<P>
   ''Oh yeah, as soon as I hit it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Torre compared it to Game 2 of the 1978 World Series, when Bob
Welch of the Dodgers struck out the Yankees' Reggie Jackson in a
nine-pitch duel that ended the game. Torre also said Jose Cardenal,
then a Yankees' coach, had O'Neill take a few steps toward
right-center after Polonia's first three fouls.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a dead silence when he hit it,'' Torre said,
remembering what it was like in the Yankees' dugout. ''I think
O'Neill slipped. I remember him banging the wall as soon as he
caught it. That will be in my mind for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
Notes: To clear space for Polonia, the Yankees' designated INF
Wilson Delgado for assignment. New York has 10 days to trade him,
put him on unconditional release waivers or send him outright to
the minors. ... New York, looking for another outfielder since
Shane Spencer tore knee ligaments July 9, still is keeping watch
for any outfielder who becomes available.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 1901 </TRAILER>
