<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congo: Peace Accord Is Invalid  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) -- The government of Congo on Thursday
pronounced a year-old peace accord dead, saying it had failed to
end two years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Interior Minister Celestin Mulumba Katshi said the
government had been forced into a deal that let foreign
''aggressors'' and the United Nations interfere in Congo's internal
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Congo no longer exists as a sovereign and free state,'' he
said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The civil war in the Central African country, formerly called
Zaire, erupted in August 1998 with a rebellion against President
Laurent Kabila, who had overthrown dictator Mobutu Sese Seko the
year before. The rebels accuse Kabila of mismanagement, corruption
and warmongering.
</P>
<P>
   A cease-fire agreement was signed in July 1999 in Lusaka, Zambia
by Kabila and his allies -- Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia -- and by
Rwanda and Uganda, who are backing the rebels. The main rebel
factions signed in the weeks that followed.
</P>
<P>
   But fighting continues, with all sides accusing each other of
violations.
</P>
<P>
   Katshi argued that the United Nations has become ''useless''
because of its ''inertia,'' complaining the world body had not
prevented what he called the slaughter of Congolese civilians by
foreign armies.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila, however, has refused to allow armed U.N. peacekeepers to
deploy in government-controlled territory. Just over 200 unarmed
U.N. military observers have deployed in Congo, out of a planned
force of 5,537 troops and observers.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila has also rejected mediation attempts by former Botswana
President Ketumile Masire.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what should replace the peace deal, Katshi said: ''All
that is required is for the aggressors to go home.''
</P>
<P>
   His comments came as the Ugandan army announced it had begun
withdrawing more than 4,000 of its troops from the northeastern
Congo town of Buta, 370 miles from the Ugandan border.
</P>
<P>
   At least 450 Ugandan troops were flown out of Buta on Wednesday
night and another 900 were scheduled to be shuttled out Thursday,
army spokesman Maj. Phinehas Katirima said in the Ugandan capital
Kampala.
</P>
<P>
   About 6,000 Ugandan troops will remain in Congo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
