<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Broncos' Mobley Faces Knee Surgery  </HEADLINE>
By AARON J. LOPEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREELEY, Colo. (AP) -- Knee surgery ended John Mobley's season in
1999. Another trip to the operating room has postponed his debut in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver Broncos linebacker was scheduled to have surgery
Friday to repair a small cartilage tear in his right knee, while
his teammates prepared for their first preseason game Saturday at
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Mobley, who tore the anterior cruciate ligament in his right
knee in Denver's second game last year, is expected to be sidelined
for about two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was really looking forward to Saturday, but I am also
relieved it's not going to go into the regular season,'' he said.
''It's something we can pretty much nip in the bud in the
preseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobley, an All-Pro in 1997, practiced in pain over the past few
days and noticed in videotapes that he was limping. An MRI on
Thursday confirmed a small meniscus tear and surgery was scheduled
at the Steadman-Hawkins Clinic in Vail.
</P>
<P>
   Team trainer Steve Antonopulos told Mobley the latest setback
was not related to last year's injury, and the 26-year-old was
determined to return for Denver's regular-season opener in St.
Louis on Sept. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unless God strikes me down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mobley has had a string of misfortune over the past 13 months.
</P>
<P>
   He pleaded guilty to driving while ability impaired and careless
driving after crashing his 1997 Jaguar last summer, and suffered
his season-ending knee injury three months later.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by his offseason rehabilitation, Mobley hoped to make
a fresh start this year only to be slowed by his knee.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just one thing after another, but it makes you
stronger,'' he said. ''I think everybody needs some kind of
adversity in their life to be able to deal with the problems as
they come.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobley's knee problems present an opportunity for rookie Ian
Gold, Denver's second-round draft pick out of Michigan. Gold and
third-year pro Nate Wayne were expected to share time at the
weakside linebacker spot.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's unfortunate that he got injured again, but I'm looking
forward to getting a chance to play,'' Gold said. ''That's why I'm
here. Due to the circumstances, I'll get some more playing time
than expected, and I'm excited.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Mobley, the Broncos also will be without
linebacker Glenn Cadrez on Saturday. Cadrez, who filled Mobley's
role last year, has a strained hamstring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
