<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Ends Up 101; Dow Ends Up 19  </HEADLINE>
By DUNSTAN PRIAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks closed higher Thursday, erasing earlier
losses as bargain hunters successfully pulled the market out of a
slump in technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, after falling as much as 137.21 in
early trading, closed up 101.42 at 3,759.88.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average also overcame early losses,
closing up 19.05 at 10,706.58. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose
13.86 to 1,452.56.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of recently beaten down stocks came back into favor,
helping to lift the broader market. Oracle was up $4.313 at $77.438
after falling as low as $71.625 and Cisco Systems rose $3.437 to
$64.375 after hitting a low of $58.50.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said technology stock prices apparently reached a
bottom Thursday and had nowhere to go but up.
</P>
<P>
   ''More than anything else, it was the thoroughly oversold
conditions that led to the rally, especially on the Nasdaq,'' said
Rao Chalasani, chief investment strategist at First Union
Securities in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   On the Dow, bellwether gainers Thursday included IBM, up $1.375
at $116.063, Intel, up $1.813 at $65.063, and J.P. Morgan, up $3 at
$135.
</P>
<P>
   Investors sold technology stocks early in the session, extending
that sector's recent losses following a string of mediocre
second-quarter earnings reports from some high-profile companies.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, a growing number of companies have warned that
earnings will probably fall off in the second half of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The latest concerns about technology earnings arose when Lehman
Brothers reported that Motorola was telling suppliers it was seeing
lower demand for handsets. That put pressure on the entire wireless
phone group. Motorola was down 68.75 cents to $36.125, while Nokia
slipped 75 cents to $40.50.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, semiconductor equipment maker Kulicke &AMP; Soffa
Industries warned that earnings later this year could fall below
forecasts. Kulicke fell $5.50 to $16.625.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq had fallen more than 14 percent in the past two weeks
amid warnings of slowing earnings growth at technology companies --
despite Thursday's turnaround many analysts believe those worries
will remain a factor in providing direction for the markets.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are still lots of concerns in the tech and telecom
sectors,'' said Ronald Hill, investment strategist at Brown
Brothers Harriman &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said the Dow was drawing some support from health care,
consumer nondurables, utilities and food and beverage stocks-- all
which tend to fare better in a slowing economy.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest gauge on inflation, orders to American factories
shot up by 5.5 percent in June, the biggest increase in nine years.
While the report suggests strong economic growth, the figure met
analyst forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few weeks, investors have tried to sort through
mixed signals about the economy, and whether or not it is slowing.
The economy's direction is critical to determine whether the
Federal Reserve will further tighten credit when its policy-makers
meet Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-4 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 1.29 billion shares,
ahead of Wednesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 0.76 at 499.45.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 2.4 percent.
Germany's DAX index was down 1.05 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was
down 1.16 percent, and France's CAC-40 was down 2.68 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
