<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Celtics Sign Brown to 3-Year Deal  </HEADLINE>
By JIMMY GOLEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. (AP) -- When Randy Brown played against the Boston
Celtics the past few years, he thought they needed someone to
bolster the second team. Someone just like him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think they're a team that's ready to burst out,'' Brown said
Thursday after signing a three-year, $7.5 million contract with the
Celtics. ''I think they're a couple of road wins away, and you're
looking at a playoff team.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, 32, played his last five seasons with Chicago, collecting
three NBA championships. He averaged 6.4 points and 2.4 rebounds in
27.5 minutes and is considered a solid defender who will fit in to
coach Rick Pitino's high-intensity system.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's someone who brings a true veteran presence that we've
been looking for for quite some time,'' said Celtics general
manager Chris Wallace, who also noted that Brown had 16 points, 11
rebounds and eight assists to help the Bulls beat the Celtics at
the FleetCenter in March.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's main job will be backing up point guard Kenny Anderson.
But he said he will try to be a team leader.
</P>
<P>
   ''I won't be a person that's going to bark in those guys' faces.
I'm not a barker,'' he said. ''I will be in their ears when they're
screwing up or doing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he also talked with Milwaukee, as well as Chicago. He
said that he won't spend a lot of time telling the players in
Boston what it was like to win championships.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've got enough tradition here,'' he said in the Hall of
Fame room of the Celtics' workout facility. Accepting a uniform
with the No. 20, he said, ''I only had about two choices with all
their numbers being retired.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics earlier failed to sign free agent Denver Nuggets
guard Tariq Abdul-Wahad. Boston is well over the salary cap -- Brown
was signed using an exception -- and was not involved in the bidding
for such prime free agents as Tim Duncan and Grant Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said the Celtics would have to get rid of Antoine Walker
and Paul Pierce to compete for the top free agents.
</P>
<P>
   ''That hasn't been an option since we've been here because we
like these guys,'' he said. ''Plus, it's a little tricky to get
down there. You have to throw a lot of things overboard, and you
don't always get those guys signed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
