<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Leaders Aim To Cut Traffic  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL FOY
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- With sooty, smoggy air hanging over the
Salt Lake area for nearly a week, Olympic organizers issued an
ambitious plan Thursday to curb traffic and air pollution during
the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our goal is to leave Salt Lake a better environment after
hosting the games,'' said Diane Conrad, director of environmental
programs for the Salt Lake Organizing Committee.
</P>
<P>
   SLOC issued her 56-page air quality plan as Conrad got
''walloped'' by the city's worst air pollution since 1989. She
stayed home Thursday nursing an aggravated sinus infection.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for 100,000 trees, natural gas-powered vans and
motor coaches for athletes, Olympic officials, sponsors and the
media and park-and-ride lots for spectators.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic sponsor General Motors will loan vehicles that can burn
gasoline or compressed natural gas. Salt Lake also will make use of
its new light-rail system.
</P>
<P>
   The environment joined sport and culture in a trio of Olympic
ideals in 1994. Salt Lake's goal is to host the first Olympic Games
with no net increase in air pollution emissions.
</P>
<P>
   Air pollution could even be reduced, although this
mountain-rimmed basin is vulnerable to wintertime temperature
inversions that can trap pollutants at ground level.
</P>
<P>
   State officials, meanwhile, are rolling out a smart traffic
management system with the overhaul of Interstate 15 along the
Wasatch Front that was designed to cut traffic accidents by 20
percent and freeway delays by 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The system involves 190 stationary cameras, 550 coordinated
traffic signals, roadbed sensors and 57 congestion-alert signs.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic committee already is a third of the way toward
planting a variety of 100,000 trees -- not seedlings but inch-thick
trees, said Conrad, former deputy commissioner for the Vermont
Department of Environmental Conservation.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers are consulting NASA images of ''urban heat islands''
to determine the best places for new trees.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta was able to reduce traffic volumes by up to 30 percent
during the 1996 Summer Games, a goal Salt Lake hopes to match.
</P>
<P>
   But controlling pollution is an ambitious goal that could be
thwarted by weather, says Robert Dalley, manager for the air
monitoring section of the Utah Division of Air Quality.
</P>
<P>
   ''Winter conversions are very common. We've had inversions
lasting up to 28 days without a break. We haven't experienced those
since 1993, so we're into seven years of better-than-usual
meteorology,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Salt Lake's summer air pollution eased slightly Thursday after
six straight days of unhealthy air. Levels for ground-level ozone,
which forms smog and can irritate lung tissue and burn eyes, and
fine particles exceeded safety standards.
</P>
<P>
   The conditions were exacerbated by 100-degree heat, stagnant air
and drifting smoke from wildfires, Dalley said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 1944 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000803.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Houston Rockets Closer to New Arena  </HEADLINE>
By MARK BABINECK
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- Reservations were expressed almost immediately
after the Houston Rockets and local officials agreed Thursday to
give Harris County voters a second chance at approving a new
downtown arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets and the Harris County-Houston Sports Authority, a
partnership between the city and Harris County, signed a letter of
agreement to build the arena moments after authority members
approved the $175 million facility. The arena's fate will now be in
the hands of voters this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ''We needed to get an agreement that was fair to both sides and
fair to the people of Houston, and I think that's what we've done
today,'' authority chairman Billy Burge said after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The authority voted eight for, none against with the Rev. C.L.
Jackson abstaining. Jackson, who is black, said he supported the
concept but was uncertain the agreement was fair to taxpayers or
that it guaranteed enough minority participation in construction
and operation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think our public will accept this,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, a $160 million arena proposal went down in flames
despite support from Mayor Lee Brown, popular former mayor Bob
Lanier and other prominent Houstonians.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the city's black community but west Harris County
Republicans, led by county party chairman Gary Polland and Tax
Assessor-Collector Paul Bettencourt, who helped build a 55 percent
landslide that buried a similar proposal last November.
</P>
<P>
   Both men were in Philadelphia for the national GOP Convention
and were not available for comment Thursday. Bettencourt planned to
reserve reaction until he had a chance to study the deal
thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets and the authority have been negotiating an
arrangement for a new arena since February. Lanier consistently
warned voters last year that the Rockets would leave if they voted
no.
</P>
<P>
   The team never has formally threatened to uproot. But a handful
of other cities have wooed the Rockets, but none of the suitors was
considered serious.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets are locked into their Compaq Center lease until
November 2003. The team wants a new building with luxury boxes and
a revenue structure more beneficial to Boca Raton, Fla.,
businessman Les Alexander, the Rockets' owner.
</P>
<P>
   The sports authority would finance construction using bonds
backed by car rental and hotel occupancy taxes, with a tentative
opening date of Sept. 1, 2003. The club will pay $105 million in
rents over a 30-year lease and be responsible for operating the
building ''in first class condition.''
</P>
<P>
   In return, the Rockets receive all revenues from events and get
at least 95 percent of the naming rights fee. Currently, the
Rockets are merely tenants at Compaq Center, the city's current
arena.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 1949 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
