<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge decides Premo was insane during 1998 shootings  </HEADLINE>
By JUDITH FORMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERNON, Conn. (AP) - A Superior Court judge ruled Thursday that
a 42-year-old Willington man was insane when he opened fire on
three state troopers responding to a 1998 vandalism call outside
his trailer home.
</P>
<P>
   In acquitting Edward Premo of attempted murder, Rockville
Superior Court Judge Jonathan J. Kaplan ruled Premo's ''severe
mental illness'' was controlling his actions on Sept. 3, 1998 when
he shot Troopers Mark Pelletier, James Reidy and Michael Hoague as
they responded to a call that Premo had backed his van into a
neighbor's van.
</P>
<P>
   All three troopers were seriously injured. Reidy now walks with
the help of a cane.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators found 16 bombs, including pipe bombs, booby traps
and various homemade grenades inside the trailer.
</P>
<P>
   Premo, an Air Force veteran who was once a probationary police
officer in Norwich, had pleaded innocent to three counts of
criminal attempt to commit murder and more than 20 charges of
manufacturing a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   The acquittal by reason of mental disease or defect came after a
one-day trial that included testimony from bomb and mental health
experts, and two of the troopers shot by Premo .
</P>
<P>
   Defense witness Kenneth Selig, a forensic psychiatrist, said
Premo suffered from a paranoia that ''had come to dominate his
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Premo thought the government, neighbors and coworkers were
conspiring against him; that he had been injected with drugs; and
that a government agent had impregnated his wife, Selig said. Premo
had put aluminum foil over all the windows in his trailer in an
effort to prevent anyone from X-raying him; had stockpiled his van
with supplies; and videotaped any routine police stop he witnessed,
Selig said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He truly and honestly believed these troopers were there to
kill him ... in his mind it was a war,'' Selig said.
</P>
<P>
   Pelletier testified that Premo told him ''I know what you
troopers are all about. I don't trust you troopers.'' Premo then
shot and wounded the officers using a semiautomatic handgun and a
rifle, Pelletier said. They returned fire, injuring Premo.
</P>
<P>
   As he and Hoague lay bleeding, Hoague asked ''Are we going to
die?,'' Pelletier recounted.
</P>
<P>
   Reidy was shot in the abdomen by a bullet the ripped through his
cruiser door.
</P>
<P>
   ''It felt like it ripped me in half,'' Reidy testified.
</P>
<P>
   The judge ordered Premo committed for further evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was obviously an explosion waiting to happen,'' Kaplan
said. He described the incident as ''a tragic and a chilling
event.''
</P>
<P>
   Premo is set to return to court Sept. 21, where he could be
ordered institutionalized for more than 100 years, Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   Reidy said he considered the ruling fair.
</P>
<P>
   ''The man was not in his right mind,'' the trooper said. ''He
wasn't shooting at me. He was shooting at the uniform.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-03-00 2055 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000803.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-NY-BRF--Missing Family-Found,0186  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KINGSTON, N.Y. (AP) - A woman who disappeared more than a month
ago with her two young children has been located in Lima, Peru,
federal authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Tania Lopez, 34, a Peruvian national who was living in
Saugerties, and her two sons, Dioson Cerron, 4, and Jortan Cerron,
2, are safe in Peru's capital city, the FBI said.
</P>
<P>
   There are still no details of how or why Lopez made her way to
South America. She was located after interviews by FBI field
officers here, in Westchester County and in places outside New York
state.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Lopez had filed a domestic violence case
against her boyfriend, Jorge Cerron, about a month before her
disappearance on July 1. Police are looking for Cerron, who also
has been missing since July 1.
</P>
<P>
   There are outstanding arrest warrants for Cerron for failure to
appear in family court and village court.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, an illegal alien, was living with Cerron, the father of
the two children. After a domestic violence incident on May 27, she
moved to a Family of Woodstock shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez was last seen on July 1 at a shopping plaza, walking her
sons in a double stroller.
</P>
</TEXT>
