<HEADLINE> Suns Re-Sign Blount to 2-Year Deal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- The Phoenix Suns re-signed backup forward-center
Corie Blount to a two-year, $3.2 million contract on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Blount, who has an option for the second year, opted out of his
existing contract after last season to test the free agent market.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bartelstein, Blount's agent, told The Arizona Republic that
several teams offered him the mid-level salary cap exception figure
of $2.25 million for next season, compared with the $1.3 million he
will get from the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's always a little scary when you walk away from more
dollars,'' Bartelstein said. ''But he feels real good about (coach)
Scott Skiles and (president) Bryan Colangelo. He feels great about
his situation here.''
</P>
<P>
   A knee injury kept Blount sidelined early last season, but he
wound up averaging 2.8 points and 3.0 rebounds in 38 games.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-year NBA veteran's playing time increased in the
playoffs, when he averaged 4.9 points and 6.2 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns also signed three other free agents -- forward Ruben
Garces, guard Justin Love and center Daniel Santiago.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-9 Garces played the last two seasons in the
Continental Basketball Association, Love is an undrafted college
player out of Saint Louis and the 7-1 Santiago played the last two
seasons in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The deals came one day after Phoenix signed backup guard Tony
Delk to a six-year contract worth nearly $17 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
