<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Duval Withdraws From International  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN MOSSMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   CASTLE ROCK, Colo. (AP) -- Just a day earlier, despite dropping
out of the pro-am after 14 holes because of a sprained lower back,
David Duval was confident he could overcome the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really don't think it's going to be a problem,'' Duval said.
</P>
<P>
   It took only six holes in Thursday's opening round of The
International for Duval to think otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Duval, runnerup in the 1999 International, was at minus-1 under
the modified Stableford scoring system used in this event when he
withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am disappointed I can't continue,'' Duval said. ''This is
one of my favorite tournaments. However, I need to get this taken
care of. Apparently, I need more rest, and I'm going to work hard
to get this resolved before the PGA championship (Aug. 17-20).''
</P>
<P>
   Duval said his back has been bothering him for about six weeks.
He was advised by doctors it might take six to eight weeks to heal.
</P>
<P>
   Duval, the world's third-ranked player, hasn't won in the past
16 months after winning four events early in the 1999 season. He
has, however, posted seven top-five finishes this year and ranks
eighth on the PGA Tour money list with $1.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   STUBBORN STUART: The key to scoring in this tournament is to --
as Tom Lehman put it -- ''really abuse the par-5s.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Stuart Appleby wasn't listening.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby totaled 14 points despite playing the four par-5s at
even par on Thursday. He had two pars and a birdie, along with a
bogey on probably the easiest par-5, the 492-yard 17th, when he
hooked his drive into a creek.
</P>
<P>
   But Appleby also eagled the par-4, 403-yard 15th, holing out a
sand wedge from 117 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ''It hit on a knob above the hole, trickled down and went right
in,'' Appleby said.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby said Castle Pines is vulnerable to good scores in its
current condition.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the quickest and smoothest I've ever seen it,'' he said.
''If the wind blows, this course can cause trouble. But it was
pretty benign this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   VIGILANT VICKERS: It's been an ongoing battle, and
International founder Jack Vickers isn't backing down.
</P>
<P>
   Vickers remains dissatisfied with his tournament's position on
the PGA Tour schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the International was played Aug. 19-22 -- the week
following the PGA championship and the week before the World Golf
Championships-NEC Invitational in Akron, Ohio. This year, the
International was moved up in the schedule, to be followed by the
Buick Open, the PGA and the WGC-NEC.
</P>
<P>
   By positioning the tournament adjacent to the PGA, Vickers
believes the International is better able to attract foreign
players, who often elect to spend more than one week in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to try to get back into the sequence that we had
before,'' Vickers said Thursday. ''And I feel very strongly that
having put the first million-dollar tournament on the Tour, we
deserve a little more consideration on this, and I'm pressing for
that.
</P>
<P>
   ''The thing that is most upsetting is it was kind of sprung on
us without due process, I think. It affected a lot of people,
including the players, who make their plans well ahead of time. So
we have been hurt in terms of some of the players that aren't here.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Tour knows I'm unhappy about this situation. I'm going to
be very persistent in pushing to get this back on track.''
</P>
<P>
   Qwest Communications Inc., which recently merged with US West,
is the presenting sponsor of the tournament. Joe Nacchio, chairman
and CEO of Qwest, said the Denver firm's sponsorship is ''a
natural'' and gives the fledgling firm both national and
international exposure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
