<HEADLINE> Thursday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressCorporate Sponsorships of Team Canada Trade Mission
Questioned
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Ladies and gentlemen, we give you Prime Minister
Jean Chretien and Team Canada -- brought to you by the Bank of
Montreal and Canada Post.
</P>
<P>
   For $50,000 each, the bank and the Crown postal corporation are
getting star billing as ''principal sponsors'' of the next
government-industry trade mission to China in November.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials say it's a logical extension of less ambitious
sponsorship arrangements made previously to help defray costs of
the popular missions.
</P>
<P>
   Critics worry it means those who spend the most money will get
privileged access to the Canadian and Chinese governments.
</P>
<P>
   ''It does sort of perpetuate the perception that big bucks from
big corporations leads to big political contact,'' Garth White, a
vice-president of the Canadian Federation of Independent Business,
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''You almost get the feeling small business need not apply.''
</P>
<P>
   Lorne Nystrom, New Democrat industry critic, agreed the
sponsorships leave the impression some businesses are elbowing
their way to the front of the lobbying line.
</P>
<P>
   The Team Canada missions, in which Chretien and provincial
premiers accompany business representatives on foreign jaunts, have
been a showpiece of Liberal trade policy since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   There was no comment from the Prime Minister's Office on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Korean Sailors Acquitted of Smuggling Chinese Migrants
</P>
<P>
   VICTORIA, British Columbia (AP) -- Nine South Korean sailors
sobbed with relief Thursday after they were acquitted of smuggling
a boatload of Chinese migrants into Canada.
</P>
<P>
   A British Columbia Supreme Court jury deliberated four days
before returning with not-guilty verdicts on five counts against
the South Korean ship's captain and his crew.
</P>
<P>
   The Koreans broke down, sobbing, after the jury delivered its
verdict and through translators thanked their lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The nine men were accused of smuggling 131 Chinese migrants into
Canada aboard a cargo ship last August.
</P>
<P>
   They have been in detention since their arrest when they tried
to flee Canadian waters after dropping the migrants on a remote
island off the northern British Columbia coast.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers insisted the sailors were forced to take part in
the human smuggling operation -- one of four that saw almost 600
Chinese migrants brought to the British Columbia coast last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Chong Un Kim, the skipper and the only accused to testify,
said the boat and crew were hijacked in the East China Sea by
so-called snakeheads.
</P>
<P>
   But Crown prosecutor Peter La Prairie questioned whether the
tale of hijacking could be believed, telling jurors Kim had failed
to mention weapons and failed to call for help once was spotted by
a Canadian Forces plane.
</P>
<P>
   The trial made legal history in British Columbia -- the first
where news cameras and microphones were allowed to record
proceedings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 2114 </TRAILER>
