<HEADLINE> Parcells Posts Bail for Financier  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Former NFL coach Bill Parcells was among
those who gathered at the federal courthouse Thursday to post bail
for former penny-stock tycoon Robert E. Brennan.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, now director of football operations for the New York
Jets, chatted about deep-sea fishing with three other associates of
Brennan while waiting for a receipt at the court clerk's office.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to speak to a reporter about Brennan, who had just
pleaded innocent to bankruptcy fraud charges at his arraignment at
federal court in Trenton.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells posted $150,000 of the $500,000 federal bail set
Tuesday after Brennan's arrest, according to a source who requested
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, of Sea Girt, coached the New York Giants to two Super
Bowl victories, and also coached the New England Patriots and the
Jets.
</P>
<P>
   He is among the members of a private golf course developed at
Brennan's former horse farm in Colts Neck, Due Process Stables,
according to people familiar with the bankruptcy case. The property
is among the assets seized to satisfy Brennan's creditors, although
Brennan still has an apartment in a gated community there.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan has been under house arrest at the property since
Tuesday while awaiting the posting of the $500,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan arrived at the Newark courthouse to finalize his bail
shortly after Parcells left.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have a lot of nice friends,'' said Brennan, a New Jersey
native whose official residence is in Juno Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed optimism about his case: ''I'm just going to deal
with it responsibly and bring it to closure.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he drove away in a green Audi convertible with Florida
plates.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan, 56, was also charged Tuesday by state authorities in
connection with his bankruptcy, and was released on $250,000 bail
soon after.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyer Michael Critchley declined to say who posted that
money.
</P>
<P>
   The two indictments unsealed with his arrest charge that Brennan
attempted to hide from creditors over $500,000 he got from cashing
casino chips less than a month after he filed for bankruptcy in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   They are the first criminal charges ever faced by Brennan after
two decades of clashes with stock regulators.
</P>
<P>
   He became known in the 1980s through his television commercials
for his former flagship brokerage, First Jersey Securities Inc.,
stepping off a helicopter and urging viewers to ''Come grow with
us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 2146 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
