<HEADLINE> Italy: No Authority for Civil Suit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Italy's supreme court has ruled that Italian courts
have no authority to hear a civil suit brought on behalf of the 20
victims who died when a U.S. Marine jet sliced through a ski
gondola cable in 1998, Italian state radio reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled that Italian civil courts had no jurisdiction
because the U.S. military was involved, RAI radio quoted lawyers
for some of the victims' families as saying. There was no
information about when the court issued the decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian news agency ANSA reported that union representatives
had attempted to bring a suit through the Italian courts to
challenge the Americans' practice of running training missions in
the Alpine area.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was brought by the union for the gondola car operator,
one of the 20 victims, ANSA said.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 3, 1998, a Marine Corps EA-6B Prowler jet sliced the
gondola cable on a training mission, sending the car's occupants
plunging 370 feet to their deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The jet's pilot, Capt. Richard Ashby, was acquitted by a U.S.
military tribunal of 20 counts of involuntary manslaughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
