<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani tells Larry King he's leaning toward radiation treatment  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Mayor Rudolph Giuliani told Larry King during
CNN's live coverage Thursday night of the Republican National
Convention that he is leaning toward radiation treatment for his
prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani told King he hadn't completely made up his mind. His
other treatment options include surgery to remove the prostate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm probably leaning toward radiation right now as the way to
do it, but haven't made a final decision yet,'' Giuliani said
during the interview broadcast from Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure was the first time the mayor has said what kind
of treatment he is contemplating since being diagnosed with
prostate cancer in May.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time that Giuliani made news this week at the
convention regarding his health. He recently told NBC's Tow Brokaw
that he has undergone hormone treatment as the first step of
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Daily News cited unidentified sources saying
Giuliani was receiving hormone therapy while trying to select a
final treatment. The newspaper said the mayor was being treated
with Lupron - a medication that blocks the production of
testosterone.
</P>
<P>
   Lupron and other hormone blockers do not cure prostate cancer,
but they can buy time for patients who want to evaluate different
therapies. Lupron's most common side effects are hot flashes and
impotence.
</P>
<P>
   Since dropping out of the U.S. Senate race against first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton on May 19, Giuliani has repeatedly refused
to answer most questions about his health.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
