<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fossella featured at GOP convention  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) - Americans should elect Texas Gov. George W.
Bush as president so Social Security and Medicare will be preserved
for future generations, U.S. Rep. Vito Fossella, R-N.Y., said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Saving Social Security is not a Republican thing or a Democrat
thing,'' Fossella said just before the Texas governor accepted the
GOP's nomination. ''It is the right thing. We need someone now who
will finally do the right thing. That someone is George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Fossella said Bush's plan to give people the option to invest
Social Security taxes in the stock market will help save the
retirement system.
</P>
<P>
   ''These options reflect the essence of America, the freedom of
individuals to save and to invest so that their future is truly
secure,'' Fossella said. ''Today, 80 million Americans are
investors. My friends, 80 million Americans can't be wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he has a personal interest in saving Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unless we act, and act now, my young sons, Dylan and Griffin,
will not see the promise of Social Security fulfilled,'' Fossella
said. ''And I refuse to let that happen. We must save Social
Security now or future generations will face certain insecurity
later.''
</P>
<P>
   He said earlier: ''I'm really thankful and grateful to the
people of Staten Island and Brooklyn who have given me their trust
and I'm really up there representing them. I hope to make them
proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Fossella, elected in 1997 to fill the unfinished term of Susan
Molinari, cited another personal interest in saving Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   Fossella's great-grandfather, Staten Island Rep. James O'Leary,
D-N.Y., was in Congress from 1935 to 1944 and was among the
legislators who voted to create Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ''My great-grandfather made that commitment 65 years ago when he
voted to create the Social Security system while he was in Congress
and it's a promise that must be fulfilled,'' Fossella said.
</P>
<P>
   ''When my great-grandfather was in Congress, he did the right
thing for my parents and my generation,'' he said. ''We're at a
crossroads: Do we do nothing and ignore future generations or do we
maintain that promise that was made 65 years ago?''
</P>
<P>
   Fossella said the campaign organizers were the one who suggested
he use the connection with his great-grandfather in his speech.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had mentioned in passing to George Bush when he started
talking about improving Social Security that my great-grandfather
was in Congress and said 'I encourage you to keep talking about
this because it's an important subject,' so perhaps it was that
that filtered its way back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional GOP leaders haven't had much of a role in this
year's convention. When asked why a congressman from Staten Island
got a prime time speaking spot in the first place, Fossella just
smiled.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason may be Fossella's willingness to back Bush
during the raucous New York GOP primary while one of the most
powerful Republicans on Staten Island, former congressman and
current Borough President Guy Molinari, was Arizona Sen. John
McCain's state chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Fossella even ran as a Bush delegate and outpolled Molinari by
more than 1,000 votes in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   ''He did what the party needed him to do,'' GOP State Chairman
William Powers said. ''He's a great guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I urged George Bush to run about a year ago, even before the
primary,'' Fossella shrugged. ''I'm very happy I made that plea.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier that evening, Gov. George Pataki pledged all 101 of the
state's delegates to Bush. He even got in a quick dig at Hillary
Clinton's Senate campaign by quoting GOP vice presidential nominee
Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   New York is a ''state that understands when Secretary Cheney
said it was time for them to go, he meant not just Bill Clinton and
Al Gore but Bill Clinton, Al Gore and Hillary Rodham Clinton,''
said Pataki, in one of the few references in Mrs. Clinton on the
convention floor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-03-00 2211 </TRAILER>
