<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000803.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Commander Says He Needs Troops  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The U.N. commander in Sierra Leone told
the Security Council Thursday he needs many more troops quickly,
but the United States remained opposed to an immediate increase in
the 13,000-strong force.
</P>
<P>
   Indian Maj. Gen. Vijay Jetley said rebels from the Revolutionary
United Front, who took 500 U.N. peacekeepers hostage in May and
kept 233 others surrounded for 2 1/2 months, still pose a serious
danger to the U.N. force.
</P>
<P>
   ''The situation is very much under control at the moment, but
it's tense,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He told reporters that the United Nations needs ''many more
troops to be given to us as quickly as possible'' but said he did
not recommend a specific number.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council initially sent 6,000 peacekeepers to Sierra
Leone to help implement a cease-fire signed in July 1999 by the
government and rebels who terrorized Sierra Leone for eight years,
killing tens of thousands of civilians and mutilating thousands
more.
</P>
<P>
   The council raised the ceiling to 13,000 in May after the rebels
reignited the civil war. At the time, Secretary-General Kofi Annan
recommended the addition of 3,500 soldiers to help the Sierra Leone
government regain authority over territory under control of the
RUF.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke said last week the United
States believes that 13,000 troops are sufficient to do the job if
they are better equipped, and if the mission is restructured to
better deal with the hostile situation it is currently confronting.
A U.S. official reiterated this position Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   With the mandate of the U.N. force set to expire Monday, council
members agreed after Jetley's briefing to draft a resolution that
would extend it for a month.
</P>
<P>
   The British-drafted resolution, supported by the United States,
asks Annan to report to the council as soon as possible with
recommendations for restructuring and strengthening the U.N. force.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution, which is expected to be approved on Friday, will
revise the mandate of the U.N. force to respond more aggressively
to further rebel advances into government-controlled areas, help
the government extend its authority by deploying U.N. troops in
sufficient numbers at key strategic locations, and promote
conditions leading to a renewed program of disarmament and
demobilization of rebel troops.
</P>
<P>
   Jetley said, however, he did not think the mandate needed to be
changed and that recent U.N. victories securing the release of
trapped U.N. peacekeepers and rebuffing rebel advances ''proved
that the mandate is quite adequate,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
