<HEADLINE> Australian Jet Drops Dummy Missile  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARWIN, Australia (AP) -- An Australian air force jet
accidentally dropped a 300-pound dummy missile over the northern
city of Darwin, destroying a 1970s-era sport utility vehicle but
causing no injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was being restored but it's a bit past that stage now,''
Tony Travers told Australian Broadcasting Corp. Radio.
</P>
<P>
   The accident occurred as an FA-18 Hornet carrying the dummy
weapon as part of its payload was returning to base following joint
maneuvers with Australian, British and Singaporean forces.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-long training device came loose as the plane was
preparing to land, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The missile hit just outside Travers's home. He said he walked
outside after hearing a noise ''like a huge thunderclap'' and
discovered the demolished vehicle, which was owned by a friend.
</P>
<P>
   The air force said it would pay the owner for the damage.
</P>
<P>
   The accident was under investigation, said Australian exercise
commander Air Commodore Dave Dunlop.
</P>
</TEXT>
