<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans Speak in Code to Voters  </HEADLINE>
By RON FOURNIER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Integrity. Dignity. Trust. Decency.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the Republican code words for dishonor and corruption
and scandal at the White House run by Bill Clinton, with help from
Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush and his convention planners didn't attack the
president directly, not when Gore is their November target and
polls show that personal broadsides can backfire.
</P>
<P>
   So they settled on scripts woven with words meant to sting, not
bludgeon. With carefully chosen phrases, they sought to saddle Gore
with Clinton's lapses and give voters, in these times of record
prosperity and relative peace, reason to demand change.
</P>
<P>
   ''To lead this nation to a responsibility era, a president
himself must be responsible,'' the Texas governor said in accepting
the GOP nomination Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   He did not mention Clinton's impeachment, but he did not have
to. The meaning was clear when Bush raised his right hand and said,
''When I put my hand on the Bible, I will swear to not only uphold
the laws of our land, I will swear to uphold the honor and dignity
of the office to which I have been elected, so help me God.''
</P>
<P>
   The line brought delegates to their feet, whistling and clanging
noise-makers.
</P>
<P>
   He did not mention Clinton's Oval Office affair, but there was
no need -- not for parents whose children asked embarrassing
questions about their first president. ''This administration did
not teach our children. It disillusioned them,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did he need to cite the 1996 fund-raising improprieties, the
Whitewater investigation, the travel office firings, the lost legal
records, the FBI files, commodity profits or Vince Foster. ''After
all of the shouting, and all of the scandal. After all of the
bitterness and broken faith, we can begin again,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Again and again, all week, convention speakers reminded voters
that the Clinton-Gore administration has created controversy as
well as economic prosperity. Their strategy: Gives voters weary of
Clinton-Gore a plausible, comfortable alternative.
</P>
<P>
   A recent poll asked voters whether they were ''plain tired'' of
Clinton. More than half said yes, Bush's target audience.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can restore the ideals of honesty and honor that must be a
part of our national life,'' vice presidential candidate Dick
Cheney said Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   He warned that Democrats, if returned to the White House, ''will
offer more lectures, and legalism, and carefully worded denials.''
Voters were left to decide on their own whether he was referring to
Clinton's tortured definition of ''sexual relations'' or Gore's
no-controlling-legal-authority defense of questionable fund
raising.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's wife Laura talked about mothers and fathers thrusting
pictures of their children in her husband's face. ''They say to
George, 'I'm counting on you. I want my son or daughter to respect
the President of the United States of America.'''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign policy was the topic, but Bush adviser Condoleezza Rice
was not just talking about world affairs when she said, ''It all
begins in the Oval Office. George W. Bush is a man of his word.
Friend and foe will know that he tells the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dole, the party's 1996 nominee, talked about the World War
II generation and, indirectly, Clinton. ''We look to Governor Bush
and Secretary Cheney to raise our sights, and to restore honor and
dignity to our public life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Heads bowed throughout the convention hall, the Rev. Franklin
Graham closed Monday night's session with a prayer reminding
Republicans that ''we have allowed our morals to erode.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is walking a fine line, given the public's mixed feelings
about Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   While six out of 10 voters disapprove of him as a person, the
same number approve of his job performance. Gore is trying to link
himself to Clinton's public record. Bush wants to saddle Gore with
Clinton's personal flaws.
</P>
<P>
   ''People aren't losing their jobs. They're not worried about
going to war. There is no constitutional crisis facing the country.
That should make it difficult for Bush to argue for change,'' said
Paul Blanchard, political science professor at Eastern Kentucky
University. ''What he has to do is convince voters that there is a
moral crisis, and then link Gore to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans tried all week, using code words and buzz phrases.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you give me your trust,'' Bush said, ''I will honor it.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Ron Fournier is chief political writer for The
Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 2306 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000803.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Texas First Lady Honored  </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- As George W. Bush launched into the biggest
political speech yet of his career, a teary-eyed former President
Bush and wife Barbara, jumped to their feet and cheered their son
on.
</P>
<P>
   Row upon row of Bush family members, old and young, coming from
far and near, celebrated the Texas governor -- the son, brother,
father and husband and, now, the presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wife, Laura, and his 18-year-old twins, Barbara and Jenna,
leapt to his side when he was done speaking. A small legion of
Bushes lined the stage, awash in a sea of confetti and balloons,
dancing to music.
</P>
<P>
   ''My brother combines a sense of who he is with a moral compass.
... He won't be swinging in the breeze,'' said Gov. Jeb Bush of
Florida, the one the family always expected would run for the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest brother, Marvin, never envisioned such a night as
Thursday, when his brother strode across the convention stage to
roaring applause before accepting the GOP presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's someone who has been underestimated his entire political
career,'' Marvin said.
</P>
<P>
   ''People have suggested that being the son of George Bush is an
easy thing,'' he said on CBS' ''Early Show,'' hours before his
brother's moment. ''It's not. So he is a survivor and he's going to
win this election.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, George W. Bush had taken a backseat in the family while
Mrs. Bush, a former librarian and school teacher, was recognized
for her work to promote childhood learning and family reading in
her state.
</P>
<P>
   ''My experience as a mom and as an elementary school teacher
taught me how smart children really are, how eager they are to
learn and how easily we can fail them ... if we don't have high
expectations,'' said Mrs. Bush, at the tribute by the National
Federation of Republican Women.
</P>
<P>
   A cardboard prop book displaying her name and rows of school-age
children framed the stage.
</P>
<P>
   She was introduced by her husband, who called his wife a great
mother ''and if all goes well, a fabulous first lady for America.''
</P>
<P>
   He also praised her convention keynote hours before delivering
his own: ''Laura certainly raised the bar, if you know what I
mean.''
</P>
<P>
   Another family member -- budding political star George P. Bush --
prepped the convention crowds Thursday night for his uncle's
remarks with an address laced with Spanish phrases.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates cheered as Rep. Jennifer Dunn of Washington introduced
him as ''one of People magazine's top 100 most eligible
bachelors.'' She hastened to add: ''Beyond the dashing good looks
and the very charming personality, meet a young man whose intellect
and heart speak volumes about why this country desperately needs
the leadership that only his uncle can provide.''
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old George P. said his uncle would create a nation
where all people ''can share in the promise and the prosperity of
el sueno Americano -- the American dream.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of the Florida governor and his Mexican-born wife
Columba, George P. also painted his uncle as a candidate seeking to
represent a more diverse nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor would be a ''a leader who really cares about
those he was elected to serve, including those of us whose faces
look different,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now is the time to make sure the American dream touches every
willing heart, no matter the color of your skin or the accent of
your speech,'' said George P., who has toured the nation addressing
young and Hispanic voters. ''I respect leaders who respect my
heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   A former teacher in Homestead, Fla., the young Bush said he
believes the Texas governor can improve education, giving schools
and families the tools they need. He also called for an end to the
cynicism and fighting in Washington, saying it is ''time to restore
a sense of honor and decency to the White House.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
