<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Power of Police Searches Narrowed  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID KRAVETS
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A federal appeals panel Thursday narrowed
the power of police to search the homes of hundreds of thousands of
California criminals who are on probation and suspected of federal
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel of the U.S. 9th Circuit Court of Appeals
wrote that probationers' homes can only be searched under the terms
of probation. They cannot be searched as a ''mere subterfuge'' for
the pursuit of new criminal investigations.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision effectively rebuffs a state Supreme Court
decision last year that officers can go into the homes on a pretext
-- even looking for evidence against a probationer's roommates --
without a search warrant.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling is binding only on the federal courts in the 9th
Circuit, but could undo the California Supreme Court's decision
because defendants in state courts who were the subjects of such
searches could petition a federal court to hear their case.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Federal Public Defender Hilary A. Fox said such a
request likely would be granted. ''We're thrilled with the
decision,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Martha Boersch, the federal prosecutor
in the case, did not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1998 case, authorities raided the home of Mark Knights to
search for evidence that he had conspired to firebomb Pacific Gas
and Electric Co. facilities as revenge for his electricity being
disconnected.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge threw out their findings on grounds that
authorities used his probation status on a state misdemeanor drug
conviction as a pretext to search his home without a warrant, and
the 9th Circuit Court of Appeals agreed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
