<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tenn. GOP in Philly on Primary Day  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE WILLIAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- A lackluster election with few contested
races drew few voters to the polls but produced a close Democratic
primary in the U.S. Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   John Jay Hooker, a 67-year-old self-described political gadfly
who has lost three previous governor's races and three U.S. Senate
contests, opposed four other challengers in Thursday's primary.
</P>
<P>
   With no money, no campaign organization and no support from
state party leaders, Hooker hoped to take on incumbent Republican
Sen. Bill Frist.
</P>
<P>
   But Middle Tennessee State University professor Jeff Clark of
Murfreesboro was giving Hooker a good run.
</P>
<P>
   With 70 percent of 2,444 precincts reporting unofficial results,
Hooker had 43,858 votes, or 34 percent, to 43,241 votes, or 33
percent, for Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Frist, who had no opposition, wasted no time in declaring his
primary victory from Philadelphia, where he gave a GOP convention
speech on health care about the same times the polls closed at
home.
</P>
<P>
   ''I look forward to reaching out to all Tennesseans in the
coming months,'' he said in a statement released 10 minutes after
the polls closed.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of Tennessee's nine congressmen -- Rep. John Tanner, a
Democrat representing the 8th District -- had an opponent on the
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   With 61 percent of 342 precincts reporting unofficial results,
Tanner had 19,577, or 86 percent, to 3,065 votes, or 14 percent for
union activist Marvin Williams of Troy.
</P>
<P>
   Low turnout was reported in most areas. Brook Thompson, state
elections coordinator, estimated turnout at 20 to 30 percent of the
state's nearly 3 million voters.
</P>
<P>
   Hooker, an eccentric Nashville lawyer, is running on one issue:
campaign finance reform. He says money is destroying the democratic
process and campaign contributions are bribes.
</P>
<P>
   He has made and lost millions in various business endeavors. He
was a founder of the Minnie Pearl fried chicken restaurant chain,
chairman of STP and United Press International, and publisher of
the now-defunct Nashville Banner.
</P>
<P>
   All 99 state House seats and 17 of 33 Senate seats were up for
election. The most contested races were for seats held by retiring
lawmakers. Two senators and five representatives did not seek
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most sought after seats was Senate District 25, where
six Democrats were vying to replace Pete Springer, who died in
April.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 2345 </TRAILER>
