<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Texas Democrat's Widow Praises Bush  </HEADLINE>
By CONNIE CASS
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The widow of one of Texas' best-known
Democratic politicians praised GOP nominee George W. Bush on
Thursday as a governor willing to ''lay aside politics'' and work
across party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Claiming a ''unique nonpartisan perspective,'' Jan Bullock said
she joined the Republican convention lineup as part of husband Bob
Bullock's ''unfinished business.''
</P>
<P>
   ''You may wonder what in the world the widow of a Texas Democrat
is doing at the Republican convention,'' Bullock told delegates.
''Did I possibly take a wrong turn?'' The delegates quickly
shouted: ''No!''
</P>
<P>
   Her late husband, the lieutenant governor, surprised his party
by endorsing Bush's re-election as governor in 1998. He died last
year at age 69, after serving 40 years in Texas politics.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats complained the speech was misleading because
almost all of their party's Texas lawmakers support Vice President
Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bob Bullock was not the Texas Democratic Party and that is the
perception that George Bush is trying to present to the country,''
said state party chairwoman Molly Beth Malcolm. ''Bob Bullock was a
statesman who did some good things for the state of Texas, but he
wasn't necessarily that great of a Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullock, who presided over the state Senate, occasionally
endorsed the Republican in a Senate race. His widow described him
as ''tough and independent.''
</P>
<P>
   In his acceptance speech, Bush told delegates the night was
''bittersweet'' without Bullock, ''a crusty veteran of Texas
politics, and my great friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Jan Bullock said the friendship began in 1994 when candidate
Bush visited the lieutenant governor at home.
</P>
<P>
   ''George said that when elected governor, he would lay aside
politics to work for the good of our state,'' she said. Her husband
''was wary.''
</P>
<P>
   ''But sure enough, as promised, the Bush administration did
bring an era of statesmanship and cooperation,'' said Bullock, who
calls herself a political independent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
