<HEADLINE> Union Protests Lead to Citations  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Thirty-five people were cited Thursday by
police in riot gear when demonstrators swarmed a downtown
intersection in front of a hotel where workers have been trying to
unionize for more than six years.
</P>
<P>
   The citations were for misdemeanor failure to disperse from the
New Otani Hotel, said police Officer Don Cox. The 35 were given
court dates and released from a mobile police booking unit at the
scene, Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred Otani hotel workers and members of the Hotel &AMP;
Restaurant Employees Union gathered during the 5 p.m. rush hour,
and some began to block an intersection.
</P>
<P>
   A call and page to union spokesman David Koff were not returned,
but the union said in a news release that it plans a series of
pickets leading up to the Aug. 14-17 Democratic National
Convention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-03-00 2358 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
